1496 /** Given a `schema` will return an inner schema that for an array item. This is computed differently based on the
1497  * `additionalItems` enum and the value of `idx`. There are four possible returns:
1498  * 1. If `idx` is >= 0, then if `schema.items` is an array the `idx`th element of the array is returned if it is a valid
1499  *    index and not a boolean, otherwise it falls through to 3.
1500  * 2. If `schema.items` is not an array AND truthy and not a boolean, then `schema.items` is returned since it actually
1501  *    is a schema, otherwise it falls through to 3.
1502  * 3. If `additionalItems` is not `AdditionalItemsHandling.Ignore` and `schema.additionalItems` is an object, then
1503  *    `schema.additionalItems` is returned since it actually is a schema, otherwise it falls through to 4.
1504  * 4. {} is returned representing an empty schema
1505  *
1506  * @param schema - The schema from which to get the particular item
1507  * @param [additionalItems=AdditionalItemsHandling.Ignore] - How do we want to handle additional items?
1508  * @param [idx=-1] - Index, if non-negative, will be used to return the idx-th element in a `schema.items` array
1509  * @returns - The best fit schema object from the `schema` given the `additionalItems` and `idx` modifiers
1510  */
1511 function getInnerSchemaForArrayItem(schema, additionalItems = AdditionalItemsHandling.Ignore, idx = -1) {
1512     if (idx >= 0) {
1513         if (Array.isArray(schema.items) && idx < schema.items.length) {
1514             const item = schema.items[idx];
1515             if (typeof item !== 'boolean') {
1516                 return item;
1517             }
1518         }
1519     }
1520     else if (schema.items && !Array.isArray(schema.items) && typeof schema.items !== 'boolean') {
1521         return schema.items;
1522     }
1523     if (additionalItems !== AdditionalItemsHandling.Ignore && isObject(schema.additionalItems)) {
1524         return schema.additionalItems;
1525     }
1526     return {};
1527 }
1528 /** Either add `computedDefault` at `key` into `obj` or not add it based on its value, the value of
1529  * `includeUndefinedValues`, the value of `emptyObjectFields` and if its parent field is required. Generally undefined
1530  * `computedDefault` values are added only when `includeUndefinedValues` is either true/"excludeObjectChildren". If `
1531  * includeUndefinedValues` is false and `emptyObjectFields` is not "skipDefaults", then non-undefined and non-empty-object
1532  * values will be added based on certain conditions.
1533  *
1534  * @param obj - The object into which the computed default may be added
1535  * @param key - The key into the object at which the computed default may be added
1536  * @param computedDefault - The computed default value that maybe should be added to the obj
1537  * @param includeUndefinedValues - Optional flag, if true, cause undefined values to be added as defaults.
1538  *          If "excludeObjectChildren", cause undefined values for this object and pass `includeUndefinedValues` as
1539  *          false when computing defaults for any nested object properties. If "allowEmptyObject", prevents undefined
1540  *          values in this object while allow the object itself to be empty and passing `includeUndefinedValues` as
1541  *          false when computing defaults for any nested object properties.
1542  * @param isParentRequired - The optional boolean that indicates whether the parent field is required
1543  * @param requiredFields - The list of fields that are required
1544  * @param experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior - Optional configuration object, if provided, allows users to override
1545  *        default form state behavior
1546  */
1547 function maybeAddDefaultToObject(obj, key, computedDefault, includeUndefinedValues, isParentRequired, requiredFields = [], experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior = {}) {
1548     const { emptyObjectFields = 'populateAllDefaults' } = experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior;
1549     if (includeUndefinedValues) {
1550         obj[key] = computedDefault;
1551     }
1552     else if (emptyObjectFields !== 'skipDefaults') {
1553         if (isObject(computedDefault)) {
1554             // If isParentRequired is undefined, then we are at the root level of the schema so defer to the requiredness of
1555             // the field key itself in the `requiredField` list
1556             const isSelfOrParentRequired = isParentRequired === undefined ? requiredFields.includes(key) : isParentRequired;
1557             // Store computedDefault if it's a non-empty object(e.g. not {}) and satisfies certain conditions
1558             // Condition 1: If computedDefault is not empty or if the key is a required field
1559             // Condition 2: If the parent object is required or emptyObjectFields is not 'populateRequiredDefaults'
1560             if ((!isEmpty_default()(computedDefault) || requiredFields.includes(key)) &&
1561                 (isSelfOrParentRequired || emptyObjectFields !== 'populateRequiredDefaults')) {
1562                 obj[key] = computedDefault;
1563             }
1564         }
1565         else if (
1566         // Store computedDefault if it's a defined primitive (e.g., true) and satisfies certain conditions
1567         // Condition 1: computedDefault is not undefined
1568         // Condition 2: If emptyObjectFields is 'populateAllDefaults' or if the key is a required field
1569         computedDefault !== undefined &&
1570             (emptyObjectFields === 'populateAllDefaults' || requiredFields.includes(key))) {
1571             obj[key] = computedDefault;
1572         }
1573     }
1574 }
1575 /** Computes the defaults for the current `schema` given the `rawFormData` and `parentDefaults` if any. This drills into
1576  * each level of the schema, recursively, to fill out every level of defaults provided by the schema.
1577  *
1578  * @param validator - an implementation of the `ValidatorType` interface that will be used when necessary
1579  * @param rawSchema - The schema for which the default state is desired
1580  * @param [props] - Optional props for this function
1581  * @param [props.parentDefaults] - Any defaults provided by the parent field in the schema
1582  * @param [props.rootSchema] - The options root schema, used to primarily to look up `$ref`s
1583  * @param [props.rawFormData] - The current formData, if any, onto which to provide any missing defaults
1584  * @param [props.includeUndefinedValues=false] - Optional flag, if true, cause undefined values to be added as defaults.
1585  *          If "excludeObjectChildren", cause undefined values for this object and pass `includeUndefinedValues` as
1586  *          false when computing defaults for any nested object properties.
1587  * @param [props._recurseList=[]] - The list of ref names currently being recursed, used to prevent infinite recursion
1588  * @param [props.experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior] Optional configuration object, if provided, allows users to override default form state behavior
1589  * @param [props.required] - Optional flag, if true, indicates this schema was required in the parent schema.
1590  * @returns - The resulting `formData` with all the defaults provided
1591  */
1592 function computeDefaults(validator, rawSchema, { parentDefaults, rawFormData, rootSchema = {}, includeUndefinedValues = false, _recurseList = [], experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior = undefined, required, } = {}) {
1593     var _a, _b;
1594     const formData = (isObject(rawFormData) ? rawFormData : {});
1595     const schema = isObject(rawSchema) ? rawSchema : {};
1596     // Compute the defaults recursively: give highest priority to deepest nodes.
1597     let defaults = parentDefaults;
1598     // If we get a new schema, then we need to recompute defaults again for the new schema found.
1599     let schemaToCompute = null;
1600     let updatedRecurseList = _recurseList;
1601     if (isObject(defaults) && isObject(schema.default)) {
1602         // For object defaults, only override parent defaults that are defined in
1603         // schema.default.
1604         defaults = mergeObjects(defaults, schema.default);
1605     }
1606     else if (DEFAULT_KEY in schema) {
1607         defaults = schema.default;
1608     }
1609     else if (REF_KEY in schema) {
1610         const refName = schema[REF_KEY];
1611         // Use referenced schema defaults for this node.
1612         if (!_recurseList.includes(refName)) {
1613             updatedRecurseList = _recurseList.concat(refName);
1614             schemaToCompute = findSchemaDefinition(refName, rootSchema);
1615         }
1616     }
1617     else if (DEPENDENCIES_KEY in schema) {
1618         const resolvedSchema = resolveDependencies(validator, schema, rootSchema, false, [], formData);
1619         schemaToCompute = resolvedSchema[0]; // pick the first element from resolve dependencies
1620     }
1621     else if (isFixedItems(schema)) {
1622         defaults = schema.items.map((itemSchema, idx) => computeDefaults(validator, itemSchema, {
1623             rootSchema,
1624             includeUndefinedValues,
1625             _recurseList,
1626             experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior,
1627             parentDefaults: Array.isArray(parentDefaults) ? parentDefaults[idx] : undefined,
1628             rawFormData: formData,
1629             required,
1630         }));
1631     }
1632     else if (ONE_OF_KEY in schema) {
1633         const { oneOf, ...remaining } = schema;
1634         if (oneOf.length === 0) {
1635             return undefined;
1636         }
1637         const discriminator = getDiscriminatorFieldFromSchema(schema);
1638         schemaToCompute = oneOf[getClosestMatchingOption(validator, rootSchema, isEmpty_default()(formData) ? undefined : formData, oneOf, 0, discriminator)];
1639         schemaToCompute = mergeSchemas(remaining, schemaToCompute);
1640     }
1641     else if (ANY_OF_KEY in schema) {
1642         const { anyOf, ...remaining } = schema;
1643         if (anyOf.length === 0) {
1644             return undefined;
1645         }
1646         const discriminator = getDiscriminatorFieldFromSchema(schema);
1647         schemaToCompute = anyOf[getClosestMatchingOption(validator, rootSchema, isEmpty_default()(formData) ? undefined : formData, anyOf, 0, discriminator)];
1648         schemaToCompute = mergeSchemas(remaining, schemaToCompute);
1649     }
1650     if (schemaToCompute) {
1651         return computeDefaults(validator, schemaToCompute, {
1652             rootSchema,
1653             includeUndefinedValues,
1654             _recurseList: updatedRecurseList,
1655             experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior,
1656             parentDefaults: defaults,
1657             rawFormData: formData,
1658             required,
1659         });
1660     }
1661     // No defaults defined for this node, fallback to generic typed ones.
1662     if (defaults === undefined) {
1663         defaults = schema.default;
1664     }
1665     switch (getSchemaType(schema)) {
1666         // We need to recurse for object schema inner default values.
1667         case 'object': {
1668             // This is a custom addition that fixes this issue:
1669             // https://github.com/rjsf-team/react-jsonschema-form/issues/3832
1670             const retrievedSchema = (experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior === null || experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior === void 0 ? void 0 : experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior.allOf) === 'populateDefaults' && ALL_OF_KEY in schema
1671                 ? retrieveSchema(validator, schema, rootSchema, formData)
1672                 : schema;
1673             const objectDefaults = Object.keys(retrievedSchema.properties || {}).reduce((acc, key) => {
1674                 var _a;
1675                 // Compute the defaults for this node, with the parent defaults we might
1676                 // have from a previous run: defaults[key].
1677                 const computedDefault = computeDefaults(validator, get_default()(retrievedSchema, [PROPERTIES_KEY, key]), {
1678                     rootSchema,
1679                     _recurseList,
1680                     experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior,
1681                     includeUndefinedValues: includeUndefinedValues === true,
1682                     parentDefaults: get_default()(defaults, [key]),
1683                     rawFormData: get_default()(formData, [key]),
1684                     required: (_a = retrievedSchema.required) === null || _a === void 0 ? void 0 : _a.includes(key),
1685                 });
1686                 maybeAddDefaultToObject(acc, key, computedDefault, includeUndefinedValues, required, retrievedSchema.required, experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior);
1687                 return acc;
1688             }, {});
1689             if (retrievedSchema.additionalProperties) {
1690                 // as per spec additionalProperties may be either schema or boolean
1691                 const additionalPropertiesSchema = isObject(retrievedSchema.additionalProperties)
1692                     ? retrievedSchema.additionalProperties
1693                     : {};
1694                 const keys = new Set();
1695                 if (isObject(defaults)) {
1696                     Object.keys(defaults)
1697                         .filter((key) => !retrievedSchema.properties || !retrievedSchema.properties[key])
1698                         .forEach((key) => keys.add(key));
1699                 }
1700                 const formDataRequired = [];
1701                 Object.keys(formData)
1702                     .filter((key) => !retrievedSchema.properties || !retrievedSchema.properties[key])
1703                     .forEach((key) => {
1704                     keys.add(key);
1705                     formDataRequired.push(key);
1706                 });
1707                 keys.forEach((key) => {
1708                     var _a;
1709                     const computedDefault = computeDefaults(validator, additionalPropertiesSchema, {
1710                         rootSchema,
1711                         _recurseList,
1712                         experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior,
1713                         includeUndefinedValues: includeUndefinedValues === true,
1714                         parentDefaults: get_default()(defaults, [key]),
1715                         rawFormData: get_default()(formData, [key]),
1716                         required: (_a = retrievedSchema.required) === null || _a === void 0 ? void 0 : _a.includes(key),
1717                     });
1718                     // Since these are additional properties we don't need to add the `experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior` prop
1719                     maybeAddDefaultToObject(objectDefaults, key, computedDefault, includeUndefinedValues, required, formDataRequired);
1720                 });
1721             }
1722             return objectDefaults;
1723         }
1724         case 'array': {
1725             const neverPopulate = ((_a = experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior === null || experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior === void 0 ? void 0 : experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior.arrayMinItems) === null || _a === void 0 ? void 0 : _a.populate) === 'never';
1726             const ignoreMinItemsFlagSet = ((_b = experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior === null || experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior === void 0 ? void 0 : experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior.arrayMinItems) === null || _b === void 0 ? void 0 : _b.populate) === 'requiredOnly';
1727             // Inject defaults into existing array defaults
1728             if (Array.isArray(defaults)) {
1729                 defaults = defaults.map((item, idx) => {
1730                     const schemaItem = getInnerSchemaForArrayItem(schema, AdditionalItemsHandling.Fallback, idx);
1731                     return computeDefaults(validator, schemaItem, {
1732                         rootSchema,
1733                         _recurseList,
1734                         experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior,
1735                         parentDefaults: item,
1736                         required,
1737                     });
1738                 });
1739             }
1740             // Deeply inject defaults into already existing form data
1741             if (Array.isArray(rawFormData)) {
1742                 const schemaItem = getInnerSchemaForArrayItem(schema);
1743                 if (neverPopulate) {
1744                     defaults = rawFormData;
1745                 }
1746                 else {
1747                     defaults = rawFormData.map((item, idx) => {
1748                         return computeDefaults(validator, schemaItem, {
1749                             rootSchema,
1750                             _recurseList,
1751                             experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior,
1752                             rawFormData: item,
1753                             parentDefaults: get_default()(defaults, [idx]),
1754                             required,
1755                         });
1756                     });
1757                 }
1758             }
1759             if (neverPopulate) {
1760                 return defaults !== null && defaults !== void 0 ? defaults : [];
1761             }
1762             if (ignoreMinItemsFlagSet && !required) {
1763                 // If no form data exists or defaults are set leave the field empty/non-existent, otherwise
1764                 // return form data/defaults
1765                 return defaults ? defaults : undefined;
1766             }
1767             const defaultsLength = Array.isArray(defaults) ? defaults.length : 0;
1768             if (!schema.minItems ||
1769                 isMultiSelect(validator, schema, rootSchema) ||
1770                 schema.minItems <= defaultsLength) {
1771                 return defaults ? defaults : [];
1772             }
1773             const defaultEntries = (defaults || []);
1774             const fillerSchema = getInnerSchemaForArrayItem(schema, AdditionalItemsHandling.Invert);
1775             const fillerDefault = fillerSchema.default;
1776             // Calculate filler entries for remaining items (minItems - existing raw data/defaults)
1777             const fillerEntries = new Array(schema.minItems - defaultsLength).fill(computeDefaults(validator, fillerSchema, {
1778                 parentDefaults: fillerDefault,
1779                 rootSchema,
1780                 _recurseList,
1781                 experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior,
1782                 required,
1783             }));
1784             // then fill up the rest with either the item default or empty, up to minItems
1785             return defaultEntries.concat(fillerEntries);
1786         }
1787     }
1788     return defaults;
1789 }
1790 /** Returns the superset of `formData` that includes the given set updated to include any missing fields that have
1791  * computed to have defaults provided in the `schema`.
1792  *
1793  * @param validator - An implementation of the `ValidatorType` interface that will be used when necessary
1794  * @param theSchema - The schema for which the default state is desired
1795  * @param [formData] - The current formData, if any, onto which to provide any missing defaults
1796  * @param [rootSchema] - The root schema, used to primarily to look up `$ref`s
1797  * @param [includeUndefinedValues=false] - Optional flag, if true, cause undefined values to be added as defaults.
1798  *          If "excludeObjectChildren", cause undefined values for this object and pass `includeUndefinedValues` as
1799  *          false when computing defaults for any nested object properties.
1800  * @param [experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior] Optional configuration object, if provided, allows users to override default form state behavior
1801  * @returns - The resulting `formData` with all the defaults provided
1802  */
1803 function getDefaultFormState(validator, theSchema, formData, rootSchema, includeUndefinedValues = false, experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior) {
1804     if (!isObject(theSchema)) {
1805         throw new Error('Invalid schema: ' + theSchema);
1806     }
1807     const schema = retrieveSchema(validator, theSchema, rootSchema, formData);
1808     const defaults = computeDefaults(validator, schema, {
1809         rootSchema,
1810         includeUndefinedValues,
1811         experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior,
1812         rawFormData: formData,
1813     });
1814     if (formData === undefined || formData === null || (typeof formData === 'number' && isNaN(formData))) {
1815         // No form data? Use schema defaults.
1816         return defaults;
1817     }
1818     const { mergeExtraDefaults } = (experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior === null || experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior === void 0 ? void 0 : experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior.arrayMinItems) || {};
1819     if (isObject(formData)) {
1820         return mergeDefaultsWithFormData(defaults, formData, mergeExtraDefaults);
1821     }
1822     if (Array.isArray(formData)) {
1823         return mergeDefaultsWithFormData(defaults, formData, mergeExtraDefaults);
1824     }
1825     return formData;
1826 }

1845 /** Checks to see if the `schema` and `uiSchema` combination represents an array of files
1846  *
1847  * @param validator - An implementation of the `ValidatorType` interface that will be used when necessary
1848  * @param schema - The schema for which check for array of files flag is desired
1849  * @param [uiSchema={}] - The UI schema from which to check the widget
1850  * @param [rootSchema] - The root schema, used to primarily to look up `$ref`s
1851  * @returns - True if schema/uiSchema contains an array of files, otherwise false
1852  */
1853 function isFilesArray(validator, schema, uiSchema = {}, rootSchema) {
1854     if (uiSchema[UI_WIDGET_KEY] === 'files') {
1855         return true;
1856     }
1857     if (schema.items) {
1858         const itemsSchema = retrieveSchema(validator, schema.items, rootSchema);
1859         return itemsSchema.type === 'string' && itemsSchema.format === 'data-url';
1860     }
1861     return false;
1862 }

1871 /** Determines whether the combination of `schema` and `uiSchema` properties indicates that the label for the `schema`
1872  * should be displayed in a UI.
1873  *
1874  * @param validator - An implementation of the `ValidatorType` interface that will be used when necessary
1875  * @param schema - The schema for which the display label flag is desired
1876  * @param [uiSchema={}] - The UI schema from which to derive potentially displayable information
1877  * @param [rootSchema] - The root schema, used to primarily to look up `$ref`s
1878  * @param [globalOptions={}] - The optional Global UI Schema from which to get any fallback `xxx` options
1879  * @returns - True if the label should be displayed or false if it should not
1880  */
1881 function getDisplayLabel(validator, schema, uiSchema = {}, rootSchema, globalOptions) {
1882     const uiOptions = getUiOptions(uiSchema, globalOptions);
1883     const { label = true } = uiOptions;
1884     let displayLabel = !!label;
1885     const schemaType = getSchemaType(schema);
1886     if (schemaType === 'array') {
1887         displayLabel =
1888             isMultiSelect(validator, schema, rootSchema) ||
1889                 isFilesArray(validator, schema, uiSchema, rootSchema) ||
1890                 isCustomWidget(uiSchema);
1891     }
1892     if (schemaType === 'object') {
1893         displayLabel = false;
1894     }
1895     if (schemaType === 'boolean' && !uiSchema[UI_WIDGET_KEY]) {
1896         displayLabel = false;
1897     }
1898     if (uiSchema[UI_FIELD_KEY]) {
1899         displayLabel = false;
1900     }
1901     return displayLabel;
1902 }

1907 /** Merges the errors in `additionalErrorSchema` into the existing `validationData` by combining the hierarchies in the
1908  * two `ErrorSchema`s and then appending the error list from the `additionalErrorSchema` obtained by calling
1909  * `validator.toErrorList()` onto the `errors` in the `validationData`. If no `additionalErrorSchema` is passed, then
1910  * `validationData` is returned.
1911  *
1912  * @param validator - The validator used to convert an ErrorSchema to a list of errors
1913  * @param validationData - The current `ValidationData` into which to merge the additional errors
1914  * @param [additionalErrorSchema] - The additional set of errors in an `ErrorSchema`
1915  * @returns - The `validationData` with the additional errors from `additionalErrorSchema` merged into it, if provided.
1916  * @deprecated - Use the `validationDataMerge()` function exported from `@rjsf/utils` instead. This function will be
1917  *        removed in the next major release.
1918  */
1919 function mergeValidationData(validator, validationData, additionalErrorSchema) {
1920     if (!additionalErrorSchema) {
1921         return validationData;
1922     }
1923     const { errors: oldErrors, errorSchema: oldErrorSchema } = validationData;
1924     let errors = validator.toErrorList(additionalErrorSchema);
1925     let errorSchema = additionalErrorSchema;
1926     if (!isEmpty_default()(oldErrorSchema)) {
1927         errorSchema = mergeObjects(oldErrorSchema, additionalErrorSchema, true);
1928         errors = [...oldErrors].concat(errors);
1929     }
1930     return { errorSchema, errors };
1931 }

1938 const NO_VALUE = Symbol('no Value');
1939 /** Sanitize the `data` associated with the `oldSchema` so it is considered appropriate for the `newSchema`. If the new
1940  * schema does not contain any properties, then `undefined` is returned to clear all the form data. Due to the nature
1941  * of schemas, this sanitization happens recursively for nested objects of data. Also, any properties in the old schema
1942  * that are non-existent in the new schema are set to `undefined`. The data sanitization process has the following flow:
1943  *
1944  * - If the new schema is an object that contains a `properties` object then:
1945  *   - Create a `removeOldSchemaData` object, setting each key in the `oldSchema.properties` having `data` to undefined
1946  *   - Create an empty `nestedData` object for use in the key filtering below:
1947  *   - Iterate over each key in the `newSchema.properties` as follows:
1948  *     - Get the `formValue` of the key from the `data`
1949  *     - Get the `oldKeySchema` and `newKeyedSchema` for the key, defaulting to `{}` when it doesn't exist
1950  *     - Retrieve the schema for any refs within each `oldKeySchema` and/or `newKeySchema`
1951  *     - Get the types of the old and new keyed schemas and if the old doesn't exist or the old & new are the same then:
1952  *       - If `removeOldSchemaData` has an entry for the key, delete it since the new schema has the same property
1953  *       - If type of the key in the new schema is `object`:
1954  *         - Store the value from the recursive `sanitizeDataForNewSchema` call in `nestedData[key]`
1955  *       - Otherwise, check for default or const values:
1956  *         - Get the old and new `default` values from the schema and check:
1957  *           - If the new `default` value does not match the form value:
1958  *             - If the old `default` value DOES match the form value, then:
1959  *               - Replace `removeOldSchemaData[key]` with the new `default`
1960  *               - Otherwise, if the new schema is `readOnly` then replace `removeOldSchemaData[key]` with undefined
1961  *         - Get the old and new `const` values from the schema and check:
1962  *           - If the new `const` value does not match the form value:
1963  *           - If the old `const` value DOES match the form value, then:
1964  *             - Replace `removeOldSchemaData[key]` with the new `const`
1965  *             - Otherwise, replace `removeOldSchemaData[key]` with undefined
1966  *   - Once all keys have been processed, return an object built as follows:
1967  *     - `{ ...removeOldSchemaData, ...nestedData, ...pick(data, keysToKeep) }`
1968  * - If the new and old schema types are array and the `data` is an array then:
1969  *   - If the type of the old and new schema `items` are a non-array objects:
1970  *     - Retrieve the schema for any refs within each `oldKeySchema.items` and/or `newKeySchema.items`
1971  *     - If the `type`s of both items are the same (or the old does not have a type):
1972  *       - If the type is "object", then:
1973  *         - For each element in the `data` recursively sanitize the data, stopping at `maxItems` if specified
1974  *       - Otherwise, just return the `data` removing any values after `maxItems` if it is set
1975  *   - If the type of the old and new schema `items` are booleans of the same value, return `data` as is
1976  * - Otherwise return `undefined`
1977  *
1978  * @param validator - An implementation of the `ValidatorType` interface that will be used when necessary
1979  * @param rootSchema - The root JSON schema of the entire form
1980  * @param [newSchema] - The new schema for which the data is being sanitized
1981  * @param [oldSchema] - The old schema from which the data originated
1982  * @param [data={}] - The form data associated with the schema, defaulting to an empty object when undefined
1983  * @returns - The new form data, with all the fields uniquely associated with the old schema set
1984  *      to `undefined`. Will return `undefined` if the new schema is not an object containing properties.
1985  */
1986 function sanitizeDataForNewSchema(validator, rootSchema, newSchema, oldSchema, data = {}) {
1987     // By default, we will clear the form data
1988     let newFormData;
1989     // If the new schema is of type object and that object contains a list of properties
1990     if (has_default()(newSchema, PROPERTIES_KEY)) {
1991         // Create an object containing root-level keys in the old schema, setting each key to undefined to remove the data
1992         const removeOldSchemaData = {};
1993         if (has_default()(oldSchema, PROPERTIES_KEY)) {
1994             const properties = get_default()(oldSchema, PROPERTIES_KEY, {});
1995             Object.keys(properties).forEach((key) => {
1996                 if (has_default()(data, key)) {
1997                     removeOldSchemaData[key] = undefined;
1998                 }
1999             });
2000         }
2001         const keys = Object.keys(get_default()(newSchema, PROPERTIES_KEY, {}));
2002         // Create a place to store nested data that will be a side-effect of the filter
2003         const nestedData = {};
2004         keys.forEach((key) => {
2005             const formValue = get_default()(data, key);
2006             let oldKeyedSchema = get_default()(oldSchema, [PROPERTIES_KEY, key], {});
2007             let newKeyedSchema = get_default()(newSchema, [PROPERTIES_KEY, key], {});
2008             // Resolve the refs if they exist
2009             if (has_default()(oldKeyedSchema, REF_KEY)) {
2010                 oldKeyedSchema = retrieveSchema(validator, oldKeyedSchema, rootSchema, formValue);
2011             }
2012             if (has_default()(newKeyedSchema, REF_KEY)) {
2013                 newKeyedSchema = retrieveSchema(validator, newKeyedSchema, rootSchema, formValue);
2014             }
2015             // Now get types and see if they are the same
2016             const oldSchemaTypeForKey = get_default()(oldKeyedSchema, 'type');
2017             const newSchemaTypeForKey = get_default()(newKeyedSchema, 'type');
2018             // Check if the old option has the same key with the same type
2019             if (!oldSchemaTypeForKey || oldSchemaTypeForKey === newSchemaTypeForKey) {
2020                 if (has_default()(removeOldSchemaData, key)) {
2021                     // SIDE-EFFECT: remove the undefined value for a key that has the same type between the old and new schemas
2022                     delete removeOldSchemaData[key];
2023                 }
2024                 // If it is an object, we'll recurse and store the resulting sanitized data for the key
2025                 if (newSchemaTypeForKey === 'object' || (newSchemaTypeForKey === 'array' && Array.isArray(formValue))) {
2026                     // SIDE-EFFECT: process the new schema type of object recursively to save iterations
2027                     const itemData = sanitizeDataForNewSchema(validator, rootSchema, newKeyedSchema, oldKeyedSchema, formValue);
2028                     if (itemData !== undefined || newSchemaTypeForKey === 'array') {
2029                         // only put undefined values for the array type and not the object type
2030                         nestedData[key] = itemData;
2031                     }
2032                 }
2033                 else {
2034                     // Ok, the non-object types match, let's make sure that a default or a const of a different value is replaced
2035                     // with the new default or const. This allows the case where two schemas differ that only by the default/const
2036                     // value to be properly selected
2037                     const newOptionDefault = get_default()(newKeyedSchema, 'default', NO_VALUE);
2038                     const oldOptionDefault = get_default()(oldKeyedSchema, 'default', NO_VALUE);
2039                     if (newOptionDefault !== NO_VALUE && newOptionDefault !== formValue) {
2040                         if (oldOptionDefault === formValue) {
2041                             // If the old default matches the formValue, we'll update the new value to match the new default
2042                             removeOldSchemaData[key] = newOptionDefault;
2043                         }
2044                         else if (get_default()(newKeyedSchema, 'readOnly') === true) {
2045                             // If the new schema has the default set to read-only, treat it like a const and remove the value
2046                             removeOldSchemaData[key] = undefined;
2047                         }
2048                     }
2049                     const newOptionConst = get_default()(newKeyedSchema, 'const', NO_VALUE);
2050                     const oldOptionConst = get_default()(oldKeyedSchema, 'const', NO_VALUE);
2051                     if (newOptionConst !== NO_VALUE && newOptionConst !== formValue) {
2052                         // Since this is a const, if the old value matches, replace the value with the new const otherwise clear it
2053                         removeOldSchemaData[key] = oldOptionConst === formValue ? newOptionConst : undefined;
2054                     }
2055                 }
2056             }
2057         });
2058         newFormData = {
2059             ...(typeof data == 'string' || Array.isArray(data) ? undefined : data),
2060             ...removeOldSchemaData,
2061             ...nestedData,
2062         };
2063         // First apply removing the old schema data, then apply the nested data, then apply the old data keys to keep
2064     }
2065     else if (get_default()(oldSchema, 'type') === 'array' && get_default()(newSchema, 'type') === 'array' && Array.isArray(data)) {
2066         let oldSchemaItems = get_default()(oldSchema, 'items');
2067         let newSchemaItems = get_default()(newSchema, 'items');
2068         // If any of the array types `items` are arrays (remember arrays are objects) then we'll just drop the data
2069         // Eventually, we may want to deal with when either of the `items` are arrays since those tuple validations
2070         if (typeof oldSchemaItems === 'object' &&
2071             typeof newSchemaItems === 'object' &&
2072             !Array.isArray(oldSchemaItems) &&
2073             !Array.isArray(newSchemaItems)) {
2074             if (has_default()(oldSchemaItems, REF_KEY)) {
2075                 oldSchemaItems = retrieveSchema(validator, oldSchemaItems, rootSchema, data);
2076             }
2077             if (has_default()(newSchemaItems, REF_KEY)) {
2078                 newSchemaItems = retrieveSchema(validator, newSchemaItems, rootSchema, data);
2079             }
2080             // Now get types and see if they are the same
2081             const oldSchemaType = get_default()(oldSchemaItems, 'type');
2082             const newSchemaType = get_default()(newSchemaItems, 'type');
2083             // Check if the old option has the same key with the same type
2084             if (!oldSchemaType || oldSchemaType === newSchemaType) {
2085                 const maxItems = get_default()(newSchema, 'maxItems', -1);
2086                 if (newSchemaType === 'object') {
2087                     newFormData = data.reduce((newValue, aValue) => {
2088                         const itemValue = sanitizeDataForNewSchema(validator, rootSchema, newSchemaItems, oldSchemaItems, aValue);
2089                         if (itemValue !== undefined && (maxItems < 0 || newValue.length < maxItems)) {
2090                             newValue.push(itemValue);
2091                         }
2092                         return newValue;
2093                     }, []);
2094                 }
2095                 else {
2096                     newFormData = maxItems > 0 && data.length > maxItems ? data.slice(0, maxItems) : data;
2097                 }
2098             }
2099         }
2100         else if (typeof oldSchemaItems === 'boolean' &&
2101             typeof newSchemaItems === 'boolean' &&
2102             oldSchemaItems === newSchemaItems) {
2103             // If they are both booleans and have the same value just return the data as is otherwise fall-thru to undefined
2104             newFormData = data;
2105         }
2106         // Also probably want to deal with `prefixItems` as tuples with the latest 2020 draft
2107     }
2108     return newFormData;
2109 }

2118 /** An internal helper that generates an `IdSchema` object for the `schema`, recursively with protection against
2119  * infinite recursion
2120  *
2121  * @param validator - An implementation of the `ValidatorType` interface that will be used when necessary
2122  * @param schema - The schema for which the `IdSchema` is desired
2123  * @param idPrefix - The prefix to use for the id
2124  * @param idSeparator - The separator to use for the path segments in the id
2125  * @param [id] - The base id for the schema
2126  * @param [rootSchema] - The root schema, used to primarily to look up `$ref`s
2127  * @param [formData] - The current formData, if any, to assist retrieving a schema
2128  * @param [_recurseList=[]] - The list of retrieved schemas currently being recursed, used to prevent infinite recursion
2129  * @returns - The `IdSchema` object for the `schema`
2130  */
2131 function toIdSchemaInternal(validator, schema, idPrefix, idSeparator, id, rootSchema, formData, _recurseList = []) {
2132     if (REF_KEY in schema || DEPENDENCIES_KEY in schema || ALL_OF_KEY in schema) {
2133         const _schema = retrieveSchema(validator, schema, rootSchema, formData);
2134         const sameSchemaIndex = _recurseList.findIndex((item) => isEqual_default()(item, _schema));
2135         if (sameSchemaIndex === -1) {
2136             return toIdSchemaInternal(validator, _schema, idPrefix, idSeparator, id, rootSchema, formData, _recurseList.concat(_schema));
2137         }
2138     }
2139     if (ITEMS_KEY in schema && !get_default()(schema, [ITEMS_KEY, REF_KEY])) {
2140         return toIdSchemaInternal(validator, get_default()(schema, ITEMS_KEY), idPrefix, idSeparator, id, rootSchema, formData, _recurseList);
2141     }
2142     const $id = id || idPrefix;
2143     const idSchema = { $id };
2144     if (getSchemaType(schema) === 'object' && PROPERTIES_KEY in schema) {
2145         for (const name in schema.properties) {
2146             const field = get_default()(schema, [PROPERTIES_KEY, name]);
2147             const fieldId = idSchema[ID_KEY] + idSeparator + name;
2148             idSchema[name] = toIdSchemaInternal(validator, isObject(field) ? field : {}, idPrefix, idSeparator, fieldId, rootSchema, 
2149             // It's possible that formData is not an object -- this can happen if an
2150             // array item has just been added, but not populated with data yet
2151             get_default()(formData, [name]), _recurseList);
2152         }
2153     }
2154     return idSchema;
2155 }
2156 /** Generates an `IdSchema` object for the `schema`, recursively
2157  *
2158  * @param validator - An implementation of the `ValidatorType` interface that will be used when necessary
2159  * @param schema - The schema for which the `IdSchema` is desired
2160  * @param [id] - The base id for the schema
2161  * @param [rootSchema] - The root schema, used to primarily to look up `$ref`s
2162  * @param [formData] - The current formData, if any, to assist retrieving a schema
2163  * @param [idPrefix='root'] - The prefix to use for the id
2164  * @param [idSeparator='_'] - The separator to use for the path segments in the id
2165  * @returns - The `IdSchema` object for the `schema`
2166  */
2167 function toIdSchema(validator, schema, id, rootSchema, formData, idPrefix = 'root', idSeparator = '_') {
2168     return toIdSchemaInternal(validator, schema, idPrefix, idSeparator, id, rootSchema, formData);
2169 }

2179 /** An internal helper that generates an `PathSchema` object for the `schema`, recursively with protection against
2180  * infinite recursion
2181  *
2182  * @param validator - An implementation of the `ValidatorType` interface that will be used when necessary
2183  * @param schema - The schema for which the `PathSchema` is desired
2184  * @param [name=''] - The base name for the schema
2185  * @param [rootSchema] - The root schema, used to primarily to look up `$ref`s
2186  * @param [formData] - The current formData, if any, to assist retrieving a schema
2187  * @param [_recurseList=[]] - The list of retrieved schemas currently being recursed, used to prevent infinite recursion
2188  * @returns - The `PathSchema` object for the `schema`
2189  */
2190 function toPathSchemaInternal(validator, schema, name, rootSchema, formData, _recurseList = []) {
2191     if (REF_KEY in schema || DEPENDENCIES_KEY in schema || ALL_OF_KEY in schema) {
2192         const _schema = retrieveSchema(validator, schema, rootSchema, formData);
2193         const sameSchemaIndex = _recurseList.findIndex((item) => isEqual_default()(item, _schema));
2194         if (sameSchemaIndex === -1) {
2195             return toPathSchemaInternal(validator, _schema, name, rootSchema, formData, _recurseList.concat(_schema));
2196         }
2197     }
2198     let pathSchema = {
2199         [NAME_KEY]: name.replace(/^\./, ''),
2200     };
2201     if (ONE_OF_KEY in schema || ANY_OF_KEY in schema) {
2202         const xxxOf = ONE_OF_KEY in schema ? schema.oneOf : schema.anyOf;
2203         const discriminator = getDiscriminatorFieldFromSchema(schema);
2204         const index = getClosestMatchingOption(validator, rootSchema, formData, xxxOf, 0, discriminator);
2205         const _schema = xxxOf[index];
2206         pathSchema = {
2207             ...pathSchema,
2208             ...toPathSchemaInternal(validator, _schema, name, rootSchema, formData, _recurseList),
2209         };
2210     }
2211     if (ADDITIONAL_PROPERTIES_KEY in schema && schema[ADDITIONAL_PROPERTIES_KEY] !== false) {
2212         set_default()(pathSchema, RJSF_ADDITONAL_PROPERTIES_FLAG, true);
2213     }
2214     if (ITEMS_KEY in schema && Array.isArray(formData)) {
2215         const { items: schemaItems, additionalItems: schemaAdditionalItems } = schema;
2216         if (Array.isArray(schemaItems)) {
2217             formData.forEach((element, i) => {
2218                 if (schemaItems[i]) {
2219                     pathSchema[i] = toPathSchemaInternal(validator, schemaItems[i], `${name}.${i}`, rootSchema, element, _recurseList);
2220                 }
2221                 else if (schemaAdditionalItems) {
2222                     pathSchema[i] = toPathSchemaInternal(validator, schemaAdditionalItems, `${name}.${i}`, rootSchema, element, _recurseList);
2223                 }
2224                 else {
2225                     console.warn(`Unable to generate path schema for "${name}.${i}". No schema defined for it`);
2226                 }
2227             });
2228         }
2229         else {
2230             formData.forEach((element, i) => {
2231                 pathSchema[i] = toPathSchemaInternal(validator, schemaItems, `${name}.${i}`, rootSchema, element, _recurseList);
2232             });
2233         }
2234     }
2235     else if (PROPERTIES_KEY in schema) {
2236         for (const property in schema.properties) {
2237             const field = get_default()(schema, [PROPERTIES_KEY, property]);
2238             pathSchema[property] = toPathSchemaInternal(validator, field, `${name}.${property}`, rootSchema, 
2239             // It's possible that formData is not an object -- this can happen if an
2240             // array item has just been added, but not populated with data yet
2241             get_default()(formData, [property]), _recurseList);
2242         }
2243     }
2244     return pathSchema;
2245 }
2246 /** Generates an `PathSchema` object for the `schema`, recursively
2247  *
2248  * @param validator - An implementation of the `ValidatorType` interface that will be used when necessary
2249  * @param schema - The schema for which the `PathSchema` is desired
2250  * @param [name=''] - The base name for the schema
2251  * @param [rootSchema] - The root schema, used to primarily to look up `$ref`s
2252  * @param [formData] - The current formData, if any, to assist retrieving a schema
2253  * @returns - The `PathSchema` object for the `schema`
2254  */
2255 function toPathSchema(validator, schema, name = '', rootSchema, formData) {
2256     return toPathSchemaInternal(validator, schema, name, rootSchema, formData);
2257 }

2278 /** The `SchemaUtils` class provides a wrapper around the publicly exported APIs in the `utils/schema` directory such
2279  * that one does not have to explicitly pass the `validator`, `rootSchema`, or `experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior` to each method.
2280  * Since these generally do not change across a `Form`, this allows for providing a simplified set of APIs to the
2281  * `@rjsf/core` components and the various themes as well. This class implements the `SchemaUtilsType` interface.
2282  */
2283 class SchemaUtils {
2284     /** Constructs the `SchemaUtils` instance with the given `validator` and `rootSchema` stored as instance variables
2285      *
2286      * @param validator - An implementation of the `ValidatorType` interface that will be forwarded to all the APIs
2287      * @param rootSchema - The root schema that will be forwarded to all the APIs
2288      * @param experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior - Configuration flags to allow users to override default form state behavior
2289      */
2290     constructor(validator, rootSchema, experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior) {
2291         this.rootSchema = rootSchema;
2292         this.validator = validator;
2293         this.experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior = experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior;
2294     }
2295     /** Returns the `ValidatorType` in the `SchemaUtilsType`
2296      *
2297      * @returns - The `ValidatorType`
2298      */
2299     getValidator() {
2300         return this.validator;
2301     }
2302     /** Determines whether either the `validator` and `rootSchema` differ from the ones associated with this instance of
2303      * the `SchemaUtilsType`. If either `validator` or `rootSchema` are falsy, then return false to prevent the creation
2304      * of a new `SchemaUtilsType` with incomplete properties.
2305      *
2306      * @param validator - An implementation of the `ValidatorType` interface that will be compared against the current one
2307      * @param rootSchema - The root schema that will be compared against the current one
2308      * @param [experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior] Optional configuration object, if provided, allows users to override default form state behavior
2309      * @returns - True if the `SchemaUtilsType` differs from the given `validator` or `rootSchema`
2310      */
2311     doesSchemaUtilsDiffer(validator, rootSchema, experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior = {}) {
2312         if (!validator || !rootSchema) {
2313             return false;
2314         }
2315         return (this.validator !== validator ||
2316             !deepEquals(this.rootSchema, rootSchema) ||
2317             !deepEquals(this.experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior, experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior));
2318     }
2319     /** Returns the superset of `formData` that includes the given set updated to include any missing fields that have
2320      * computed to have defaults provided in the `schema`.
2321      *
2322      * @param schema - The schema for which the default state is desired
2323      * @param [formData] - The current formData, if any, onto which to provide any missing defaults
2324      * @param [includeUndefinedValues=false] - Optional flag, if true, cause undefined values to be added as defaults.
2325      *          If "excludeObjectChildren", pass `includeUndefinedValues` as false when computing defaults for any nested
2326      *          object properties.
2327      * @returns - The resulting `formData` with all the defaults provided
2328      */
2329     getDefaultFormState(schema, formData, includeUndefinedValues = false) {
2330         return getDefaultFormState(this.validator, schema, formData, this.rootSchema, includeUndefinedValues, this.experimental_defaultFormStateBehavior);
2331     }
2332     /** Determines whether the combination of `schema` and `uiSchema` properties indicates that the label for the `schema`
2333      * should be displayed in a UI.
2334      *
2335      * @param schema - The schema for which the display label flag is desired
2336      * @param [uiSchema] - The UI schema from which to derive potentially displayable information
2337      * @param [globalOptions={}] - The optional Global UI Schema from which to get any fallback `xxx` options
2338      * @returns - True if the label should be displayed or false if it should not
2339      */
2340     getDisplayLabel(schema, uiSchema, globalOptions) {
2341         return getDisplayLabel(this.validator, schema, uiSchema, this.rootSchema, globalOptions);
2342     }
2343     /** Determines which of the given `options` provided most closely matches the `formData`.
2344      * Returns the index of the option that is valid and is the closest match, or 0 if there is no match.
2345      *
2346      * The closest match is determined using the number of matching properties, and more heavily favors options with
2347      * matching readOnly, default, or const values.
2348      *
2349      * @param formData - The form data associated with the schema
2350      * @param options - The list of options that can be selected from
2351      * @param [selectedOption] - The index of the currently selected option, defaulted to -1 if not specified
2352      * @param [discriminatorField] - The optional name of the field within the options object whose value is used to
2353      *          determine which option is selected
2354      * @returns - The index of the option that is the closest match to the `formData` or the `selectedOption` if no match
2355      */
2356     getClosestMatchingOption(formData, options, selectedOption, discriminatorField) {
2357         return getClosestMatchingOption(this.validator, this.rootSchema, formData, options, selectedOption, discriminatorField);
2358     }
2359     /** Given the `formData` and list of `options`, attempts to find the index of the first option that matches the data.
2360      * Always returns the first option if there is nothing that matches.
2361      *
2362      * @param formData - The current formData, if any, used to figure out a match
2363      * @param options - The list of options to find a matching options from
2364      * @param [discriminatorField] - The optional name of the field within the options object whose value is used to
2365      *          determine which option is selected
2366      * @returns - The firstindex of the matched option or 0 if none is available
2367      */
2368     getFirstMatchingOption(formData, options, discriminatorField) {
2369         return getFirstMatchingOption(this.validator, formData, options, this.rootSchema, discriminatorField);
2370     }
2371     /** Given the `formData` and list of `options`, attempts to find the index of the option that best matches the data.
2372      * Deprecated, use `getFirstMatchingOption()` instead.
2373      *
2374      * @param formData - The current formData, if any, onto which to provide any missing defaults
2375      * @param options - The list of options to find a matching options from
2376      * @param [discriminatorField] - The optional name of the field within the options object whose value is used to
2377      *          determine which option is selected
2378      * @returns - The index of the matched option or 0 if none is available
2379      * @deprecated
2380      */
2381     getMatchingOption(formData, options, discriminatorField) {
2382         return getMatchingOption(this.validator, formData, options, this.rootSchema, discriminatorField);
2383     }
2384     /** Checks to see if the `schema` and `uiSchema` combination represents an array of files
2385      *
2386      * @param schema - The schema for which check for array of files flag is desired
2387      * @param [uiSchema] - The UI schema from which to check the widget
2388      * @returns - True if schema/uiSchema contains an array of files, otherwise false
2389      */
2390     isFilesArray(schema, uiSchema) {
2391         return isFilesArray(this.validator, schema, uiSchema, this.rootSchema);
2392     }
2393     /** Checks to see if the `schema` combination represents a multi-select
2394      *
2395      * @param schema - The schema for which check for a multi-select flag is desired
2396      * @returns - True if schema contains a multi-select, otherwise false
2397      */
2398     isMultiSelect(schema) {
2399         return isMultiSelect(this.validator, schema, this.rootSchema);
2400     }
2401     /** Checks to see if the `schema` combination represents a select
2402      *
2403      * @param schema - The schema for which check for a select flag is desired
2404      * @returns - True if schema contains a select, otherwise false
2405      */
2406     isSelect(schema) {
2407         return isSelect(this.validator, schema, this.rootSchema);
2408     }
2409     /** Merges the errors in `additionalErrorSchema` into the existing `validationData` by combining the hierarchies in
2410      * the two `ErrorSchema`s and then appending the error list from the `additionalErrorSchema` obtained by calling
2411      * `getValidator().toErrorList()` onto the `errors` in the `validationData`. If no `additionalErrorSchema` is passed,
2412      * then `validationData` is returned.
2413      *
2414      * @param validationData - The current `ValidationData` into which to merge the additional errors
2415      * @param [additionalErrorSchema] - The additional set of errors
2416      * @returns - The `validationData` with the additional errors from `additionalErrorSchema` merged into it, if provided.
2417      * @deprecated - Use the `validationDataMerge()` function exported from `@rjsf/utils` instead. This function will be
2418      *        removed in the next major release.
2419      */
2420     mergeValidationData(validationData, additionalErrorSchema) {
2421         return mergeValidationData(this.validator, validationData, additionalErrorSchema);
2422     }
2423     /** Retrieves an expanded schema that has had all of its conditions, additional properties, references and
2424      * dependencies resolved and merged into the `schema` given a `rawFormData` that is used to do the potentially
2425      * recursive resolution.
2426      *
2427      * @param schema - The schema for which retrieving a schema is desired
2428      * @param [rawFormData] - The current formData, if any, to assist retrieving a schema
2429      * @returns - The schema having its conditions, additional properties, references and dependencies resolved
2430      */
2431     retrieveSchema(schema, rawFormData) {
2432         return retrieveSchema(this.validator, schema, this.rootSchema, rawFormData);
2433     }

2435      * new schema does not contain any properties, then `undefined` is returned to clear all the form data. Due to the
2436      * nature of schemas, this sanitization happens recursively for nested objects of data. Also, any properties in the
2437      * old schemas that are non-existent in the new schema are set to `undefined`.
2438      *
2439      * @param [newSchema] - The new schema for which the data is being sanitized
2440      * @param [oldSchema] - The old schema from which the data originated

2443      *      to `undefined`. Will return `undefined` if the new schema is not an object containing properties.
2444      */
2445     sanitizeDataForNewSchema(newSchema, oldSchema, data) {

2456      */
2457     toIdSchema(schema, id, formData, idPrefix = 'root', idSeparator = '_') {

2459     }

2465      * @returns - The `PathSchema` object for the `schema`
2466      */
2467     toPathSchema(schema, name, formData) {

2483 ;// CONCATENATED MODULE: ../node_modules/@rjsf/utils/lib/dataURItoBlob.js
2484 /** Given the `FileReader.readAsDataURL()` based `dataURI` extracts that data into an actual Blob along with the name
2485  * of that Blob if provided in the URL. If no name is provided, then the name falls back to `unknown`.
2486  *
2487  * @param dataURI - The `DataUrl` potentially containing name and raw data to be converted to a Blob
2488  * @returns - an object containing a Blob and its name, extracted from the URI
2489  */
2490 function dataURItoBlob(dataURI) {
2491     // Split metadata from data
2492     const splitted = dataURI.split(',');
2493     // Split params
2494     const params = splitted[0].split(';');
2495     // Get mime-type from params
2496     const type = params[0].replace('data:', '');
2497     // Filter the name property from params
2498     const properties = params.filter((param) => {
2499         return param.split('=')[0] === 'name';
2500     });
2501     // Look for the name and use unknown if no name property.
2502     let name;
2503     if (properties.length !== 1) {
2504         name = 'unknown';
2505     }
2506     else {
2507         // Because we filtered out the other property,
2508         // we only have the name case here, which we decode to make it human-readable
2509         name = decodeURI(properties[0].split('=')[1]);
2510     }
2511     // Built the Uint8Array Blob parameter from the base64 string.
2512     try {
2513         const binary = atob(splitted[1]);
2514         const array = [];
2515         for (let i = 0; i < binary.length; i++) {
2516             array.push(binary.charCodeAt(i));
2517         }
2518         // Create the blob object
2519         const blob = new window.Blob([new Uint8Array(array)], { type });
2520         return { blob, name };
2521     }
2522     catch (error) {
2523         return { blob: { size: 0, type: error.message }, name: dataURI };
2524     }
2525 }

2527 ;// CONCATENATED MODULE: ../node_modules/@rjsf/utils/lib/replaceStringParameters.js
2528 /** Potentially substitutes all replaceable parameters with the associated value(s) from the `params` if available. When
2529  * a `params` array is provided, each value in the array is used to replace any of the replaceable parameters in the
2530  * `inputString` using the `%1`, `%2`, etc. replacement specifiers.
2531  *
2532  * @param inputString - The string which will be potentially updated with replacement parameters
2533  * @param params - The optional list of replaceable parameter values to substitute into the english string
2534  * @returns - The updated string with any replacement specifiers replaced
2535  */
2536 function replaceStringParameters(inputString, params) {
2537     let output = inputString;
2538     if (Array.isArray(params)) {
2539         const parts = output.split(/(%\d)/);
2540         params.forEach((param, index) => {
2541             const partIndex = parts.findIndex((part) => part === `%${index + 1}`);
2542             if (partIndex >= 0) {
2543                 parts[partIndex] = param;
2544             }
2545         });
2546         output = parts.join('');
2547     }
2548     return output;
2549 }

2566 /** Returns the value(s) from `allEnumOptions` at the index(es) provided by `valueIndex`. If `valueIndex` is not an
2567  * array AND the index is not valid for `allEnumOptions`, `emptyValue` is returned. If `valueIndex` is an array, AND it
2568  * contains an invalid index, the returned array will have the resulting undefined values filtered out, leaving only
2569  * valid values or in the worst case, an empty array.
2570  *
2571  * @param valueIndex - The index(es) of the value(s) that should be returned
2572  * @param [allEnumOptions=[]] - The list of all the known enumOptions
2573  * @param [emptyValue] - The value to return when the non-array `valueIndex` does not refer to a real option
2574  * @returns - The single or list of values specified by the single or list of indexes if they are valid. Otherwise,
2575  *        `emptyValue` or an empty list.
2576  */
2577 function enumOptionsValueForIndex(valueIndex, allEnumOptions = [], emptyValue) {
2578     if (Array.isArray(valueIndex)) {
2579         return valueIndex.map((index) => enumOptionsValueForIndex(index, allEnumOptions)).filter((val) => val);
2580     }
2581     // So Number(null) and Number('') both return 0, so use emptyValue for those two values
2582     const index = valueIndex === '' || valueIndex === null ? -1 : Number(valueIndex);
2583     const option = allEnumOptions[index];
2584     return option ? option.value : emptyValue;
2585 }

2640         .map((opt, index) => (enumOptionsIsSelected(opt.value, value) ? String(index) : undefined))
2641         .filter((opt) => typeof opt !== 'undefined');
2642     if (!multiple) {
2643         return selectedIndexes[0];
2644     }
2645     return selectedIndexes;

2653 
2654 /** Add the enum option value at the `valueIndex` to the list of `selected` values in the proper order as defined by
2655  * `allEnumOptions`
2656  *
2657  * @param valueIndex - The index of the value that should be selected
2658  * @param selected - The current list of selected values
2659  * @param [allEnumOptions=[]] - The list of all the known enumOptions
2660  * @returns - The updated list of selected enum values with enum value at the `valueIndex` added to it
2661  */
2662 function enumOptionsSelectValue(valueIndex, selected, allEnumOptions = []) {
2663     const value = enumOptionsValueForIndex(valueIndex, allEnumOptions);
2664     if (!isNil_default()(value)) {
2665         const index = allEnumOptions.findIndex((opt) => value === opt.value);
2666         const all = allEnumOptions.map(({ value: val }) => val);
2667         const updated = selected.slice(0, index).concat(value, selected.slice(index));
2668         // As inserting values at predefined index positions doesn't work with empty
2669         // arrays, we need to reorder the updated selection to match the initial order
2670         return updated.sort((a, b) => Number(all.indexOf(a) > all.indexOf(b)));
2671     }
2672     return selected;
2673 }

2683 /** The `ErrorSchemaBuilder<T>` is used to build an `ErrorSchema<T>` since the definition of the `ErrorSchema` type is
2684  * designed for reading information rather than writing it. Use this class to add, replace or clear errors in an error
2685  * schema by using either dotted path or an array of path names. Once you are done building the `ErrorSchema`, you can
2686  * get the result and/or reset all the errors back to an initial set and start again.
2687  */
2688 class ErrorSchemaBuilder {
2689     /** Construct an `ErrorSchemaBuilder` with an optional initial set of errors in an `ErrorSchema`.
2690      *
2691      * @param [initialSchema] - The optional set of initial errors, that will be cloned into the class
2692      */
2693     constructor(initialSchema) {
2694         /** The error schema being built
2695          *
2696          * @private
2697          */
2698         this.errorSchema = {};
2699         this.resetAllErrors(initialSchema);
2700     }
2701     /** Returns the `ErrorSchema` that has been updated by the methods of the `ErrorSchemaBuilder`
2702      */
2703     get ErrorSchema() {
2704         return this.errorSchema;
2705     }
2706     /** Will get an existing `ErrorSchema` at the specified `pathOfError` or create and return one.
2707      *
2708      * @param [pathOfError] - The optional path into the `ErrorSchema` at which to add the error(s)
2709      * @returns - The error block for the given `pathOfError` or the root if not provided
2710      * @private
2711      */
2712     getOrCreateErrorBlock(pathOfError) {
2713         const hasPath = (Array.isArray(pathOfError) && pathOfError.length > 0) || typeof pathOfError === 'string';
2714         let errorBlock = hasPath ? get_default()(this.errorSchema, pathOfError) : this.errorSchema;
2715         if (!errorBlock && pathOfError) {
2716             errorBlock = {};
2717             set_default()(this.errorSchema, pathOfError, errorBlock);
2718         }
2719         return errorBlock;
2720     }
2721     /** Resets all errors in the `ErrorSchemaBuilder` back to the `initialSchema` if provided, otherwise an empty set.
2722      *
2723      * @param [initialSchema] - The optional set of initial errors, that will be cloned into the class
2724      * @returns - The `ErrorSchemaBuilder` object for chaining purposes
2725      */
2726     resetAllErrors(initialSchema) {
2727         this.errorSchema = initialSchema ? cloneDeep_default()(initialSchema) : {};
2728         return this;
2729     }
2730     /** Adds the `errorOrList` to the list of errors in the `ErrorSchema` at either the root level or the location within
2731      * the schema described by the `pathOfError`. For more information about how to specify the path see the
2732      * [eslint lodash plugin docs](https://github.com/wix/eslint-plugin-lodash/blob/master/docs/rules/path-style.md).
2733      *
2734      * @param errorOrList - The error or list of errors to add into the `ErrorSchema`
2735      * @param [pathOfError] - The optional path into the `ErrorSchema` at which to add the error(s)
2736      * @returns - The `ErrorSchemaBuilder` object for chaining purposes
2737      */
2738     addErrors(errorOrList, pathOfError) {
2739         const errorBlock = this.getOrCreateErrorBlock(pathOfError);
2740         let errorsList = get_default()(errorBlock, ERRORS_KEY);
2741         if (!Array.isArray(errorsList)) {
2742             errorsList = [];
2743             errorBlock[ERRORS_KEY] = errorsList;
2744         }
2745         if (Array.isArray(errorOrList)) {
2746             errorsList.push(...errorOrList);
2747         }
2748         else {
2749             errorsList.push(errorOrList);
2750         }
2751         return this;
2752     }
2753     /** Sets/replaces the `errorOrList` as the error(s) in the `ErrorSchema` at either the root level or the location
2754      * within the schema described by the `pathOfError`. For more information about how to specify the path see the
2755      * [eslint lodash plugin docs](https://github.com/wix/eslint-plugin-lodash/blob/master/docs/rules/path-style.md).
2756      *
2757      * @param errorOrList - The error or list of errors to set into the `ErrorSchema`
2758      * @param [pathOfError] - The optional path into the `ErrorSchema` at which to set the error(s)
2759      * @returns - The `ErrorSchemaBuilder` object for chaining purposes
2760      */
2761     setErrors(errorOrList, pathOfError) {
2762         const errorBlock = this.getOrCreateErrorBlock(pathOfError);
2763         // Effectively clone the array being given to prevent accidental outside manipulation of the given list
2764         const listToAdd = Array.isArray(errorOrList) ? [...errorOrList] : [errorOrList];
2765         set_default()(errorBlock, ERRORS_KEY, listToAdd);
2766         return this;
2767     }
2768     /** Clears the error(s) in the `ErrorSchema` at either the root level or the location within the schema described by
2769      * the `pathOfError`. For more information about how to specify the path see the
2770      * [eslint lodash plugin docs](https://github.com/wix/eslint-plugin-lodash/blob/master/docs/rules/path-style.md).
2771      *
2772      * @param [pathOfError] - The optional path into the `ErrorSchema` at which to clear the error(s)
2773      * @returns - The `ErrorSchemaBuilder` object for chaining purposes
2774      */
2775     clearErrors(pathOfError) {
2776         const errorBlock = this.getOrCreateErrorBlock(pathOfError);
2777         set_default()(errorBlock, ERRORS_KEY, []);
2778         return this;
2779     }
2780 }

2783 /** Given date & time information with optional yearRange & format, returns props for DateElement
2784  *
2785  * @param date - Object containing date with optional time information
2786  * @param time - Determines whether to include time or not
2787  * @param [yearRange=[1900, new Date().getFullYear() + 2]] - Controls the list of years to be displayed
2788  * @param [format='YMD'] - Controls the order in which day, month and year input element will be displayed
2789  * @returns Array of props for DateElement
2790  */
2791 function getDateElementProps(date, time, yearRange = [1900, new Date().getFullYear() + 2], format = 'YMD') {
2792     const { day, month, year, hour, minute, second } = date;
2793     const dayObj = { type: 'day', range: [1, 31], value: day };
2794     const monthObj = { type: 'month', range: [1, 12], value: month };
2795     const yearObj = { type: 'year', range: yearRange, value: year };
2796     const dateElementProp = [];
2797     switch (format) {
2798         case 'MDY':
2799             dateElementProp.push(monthObj, dayObj, yearObj);
2800             break;
2801         case 'DMY':
2802             dateElementProp.push(dayObj, monthObj, yearObj);
2803             break;
2804         case 'YMD':
2805         default:
2806             dateElementProp.push(yearObj, monthObj, dayObj);
2807     }
2808     if (time) {
2809         dateElementProp.push({ type: 'hour', range: [0, 23], value: hour }, { type: 'minute', range: [0, 59], value: minute }, { type: 'second', range: [0, 59], value: second });
2810     }
2811     return dateElementProp;
2812 }

2815 /** Extracts the range spec information `{ step?: number, min?: number, max?: number }` that can be spread onto an HTML
2816  * input from the range analog in the schema `{ multipleOf?: number, minimum?: number, maximum?: number }`.
2817  *
2818  * @param schema - The schema from which to extract the range spec
2819  * @returns - A range specification from the schema
2820  */
2821 function rangeSpec(schema) {
2822     const spec = {};
2823     if (schema.multipleOf) {
2824         spec.step = schema.multipleOf;
2825     }
2826     if (schema.minimum || schema.minimum === 0) {
2827         spec.min = schema.minimum;
2828     }
2829     if (schema.maximum || schema.maximum === 0) {
2830         spec.max = schema.maximum;
2831     }
2832     return spec;
2833 }

2835 ;// CONCATENATED MODULE: ../node_modules/@rjsf/utils/lib/getInputProps.js
2836 
2837 /** Using the `schema`, `defaultType` and `options`, extract out the props for the <input> element that make sense.
2838  *
2839  * @param schema - The schema for the field provided by the widget
2840  * @param [defaultType] - The default type, if any, for the field provided by the widget
2841  * @param [options={}] - The UI Options for the field provided by the widget
2842  * @param [autoDefaultStepAny=true] - Determines whether to auto-default step=any when the type is number and no step
2843  * @returns - The extracted `InputPropsType` object
2844  */
2845 function getInputProps(schema, defaultType, options = {}, autoDefaultStepAny = true) {
2846     const inputProps = {
2847         type: defaultType || 'text',
2848         ...rangeSpec(schema),
2849     };
2850     // If options.inputType is set use that as the input type
2851     if (options.inputType) {
2852         inputProps.type = options.inputType;
2853     }
2854     else if (!defaultType) {
2855         // If the schema is of type number or integer, set the input type to number
2856         if (schema.type === 'number') {
2857             inputProps.type = 'number';
2858             // Only add step if one isn't already defined and we are auto-defaulting the "any" step
2859             if (autoDefaultStepAny && inputProps.step === undefined) {
2860                 // Setting step to 'any' fixes a bug in Safari where decimals are not
2861                 // allowed in number inputs
2862                 inputProps.step = 'any';
2863             }
2864         }
2865         else if (schema.type === 'integer') {
2866             inputProps.type = 'number';
2867             // Only add step if one isn't already defined
2868             if (inputProps.step === undefined) {
2869                 // Since this is integer, you always want to step up or down in multiples of 1
2870                 inputProps.step = 1;
2871             }
2872         }
2873     }
2874     if (options.autocomplete) {
2875         inputProps.autoComplete = options.autocomplete;
2876     }
2877     return inputProps;
2878 }

2907 /** Returns the template with the given `name` from either the `uiSchema` if it is defined or from the `registry`

2993 /** Wraps the given widget with stateless functional component that will merge any `defaultProps.options` with the
2994  * `options` that are provided in the props. It will add the wrapper component as a `MergedWidget` property onto the
2995  * `Widget` so that future attempts to wrap `AWidget` will return the already existing wrapper.
2996  *
2997  * @param AWidget - A widget that will be wrapped or one that is already wrapped
2998  * @returns - The wrapper widget
2999  */
3000 function mergeWidgetOptions(AWidget) {
3001     let MergedWidget = get_default()(AWidget, 'MergedWidget');
3002     // cache return value as property of widget for proper react reconciliation
3003     if (!MergedWidget) {
3004         const defaultOptions = (AWidget.defaultProps && AWidget.defaultProps.options) || {};
3005         MergedWidget = ({ options, ...props }) => {
3006             return (0,jsx_runtime.jsx)(AWidget, { options: { ...defaultOptions, ...options }, ...props });
3007         };
3008         set_default()(AWidget, 'MergedWidget', MergedWidget);
3009     }
3010     return MergedWidget;
3011 }
3012 /** Given a schema representing a field to render and either the name or actual `Widget` implementation, returns the
3013  * React component that is used to render the widget. If the `widget` is already a React component, then it is wrapped
3014  * with a `MergedWidget`. Otherwise an attempt is made to look up the widget inside of the `registeredWidgets` map based
3015  * on the schema type and `widget` name. If no widget component can be found an `Error` is thrown.
3016  *
3017  * @param schema - The schema for the field
3018  * @param [widget] - Either the name of the widget OR a `Widget` implementation to use
3019  * @param [registeredWidgets={}] - A registry of widget name to `Widget` implementation
3020  * @returns - The `Widget` component to use
3021  * @throws - An error if there is no `Widget` component that can be returned
3022  */
3023 function getWidget(schema, widget, registeredWidgets = {}) {
3024     const type = getSchemaType(schema);
3025     if (typeof widget === 'function' ||
3026         (widget && react_is.isForwardRef((0,index_js_.createElement)(widget))) ||
3027         react_is.isMemo(widget)) {
3028         return mergeWidgetOptions(widget);
3029     }
3030     if (typeof widget !== 'string') {
3031         throw new Error(`Unsupported widget definition: ${typeof widget}`);
3032     }
3033     if (widget in registeredWidgets) {
3034         const registeredWidget = registeredWidgets[widget];
3035         return getWidget(schema, registeredWidget, registeredWidgets);
3036     }
3037     if (typeof type === 'string') {
3038         if (!(type in widgetMap)) {
3039             throw new Error(`No widget for type '${type}'`);
3040         }
3041         if (widget in widgetMap[type]) {
3042             const registeredWidget = registeredWidgets[widgetMap[type][widget]];
3043             return getWidget(schema, registeredWidget, registeredWidgets);
3044         }
3045     }
3046     throw new Error(`No widget '${widget}' for type '${type}'`);
3047 }

3049 ;// CONCATENATED MODULE: ../node_modules/@rjsf/utils/lib/hashForSchema.js
3050 /** JS has no built-in hashing function, so rolling our own
3051  *  based on Java's hashing fn:
3052  *  http://www.java2s.com/example/nodejs-utility-method/string-hash/hashcode-4dc2b.html
3053  *
3054  * @param string - The string for which to get the hash
3055  * @returns - The resulting hash of the string in hex format
3056  */
3057 function hashString(string) {
3058     let hash = 0;
3059     for (let i = 0; i < string.length; i += 1) {
3060         const chr = string.charCodeAt(i);
3061         hash = (hash << 5) - hash + chr;
3062         hash = hash & hash; // Convert to 32bit integer
3063     }
3064     return hash.toString(16);
3065 }
3066 /** Stringifies the schema and returns the hash of the resulting string. Sorts schema fields
3067  * in consistent order before stringify to prevent different hash ids for the same schema.
3068  *
3069  * @param schema - The schema for which the hash is desired
3070  * @returns - The string obtained from the hash of the stringified schema
3071  */
3072 function hashForSchema(schema) {
3073     const allKeys = new Set();
3074     // solution source: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/16167581/sort-object-properties-and-json-stringify/53593328#53593328
3075     JSON.stringify(schema, (key, value) => (allKeys.add(key), value));
3076     return hashString(JSON.stringify(schema, Array.from(allKeys).sort()));
3077 }

3081 /** Detects whether the `widget` exists for the `schema` with the associated `registryWidgets` and returns true if it
3082  * does, or false if it doesn't.
3083  *
3084  * @param schema - The schema for the field
3085  * @param widget - Either the name of the widget OR a `Widget` implementation to use
3086  * @param [registeredWidgets={}] - A registry of widget name to `Widget` implementation
3087  * @returns - True if the widget exists, false otherwise
3088  */
3089 function hasWidget(schema, widget, registeredWidgets = {}) {
3090     try {
3091         getWidget(schema, widget, registeredWidgets);
3092         return true;
3093     }
3094     catch (e) {
3095         const err = e;
3096         if (err.message && (err.message.startsWith('No widget') || err.message.startsWith('Unsupported widget'))) {
3097             return false;
3098         }
3099         throw e;
3100     }
3101 }
