3213 /** Gets the list of options from the schema. If the schema has an enum list, then those enum values are returned. The
3214  * labels for the options will be extracted from the non-standard, RJSF-deprecated `enumNames` if it exists, otherwise
3215  * the label will be the same as the `value`. If the schema has a `oneOf` or `anyOf`, then the value is the list of
3216  * `const` values from the schema and the label is either the `schema.title` or the value.
3217  *
3218  * @param schema - The schema from which to extract the options list
3219  * @returns - The list of options from the schema
3220  */
3221 function optionsList(schema) {
3222     // enumNames was deprecated in v5 and is intentionally omitted from the RJSFSchema type.
3223     // Cast the type to include enumNames so the feature still works.
3224     const schemaWithEnumNames = schema;
3225     if (schemaWithEnumNames.enumNames && "production" !== 'production') {}
3226     if (schema.enum) {
3227         return schema.enum.map((value, i) => {
3228             const label = (schemaWithEnumNames.enumNames && schemaWithEnumNames.enumNames[i]) || String(value);
3229             return { label, value };
3230         });
3231     }
3232     const altSchemas = schema.oneOf || schema.anyOf;
3233     return (altSchemas &&
3234         altSchemas.map((aSchemaDef) => {
3235             const aSchema = aSchemaDef;
3236             const value = toConstant(aSchema);
3237             const label = aSchema.title || String(value);
3238             return {
3239                 schema: aSchema,
3240                 label,
3241                 value,
3242             };
3243         }));
3244 }

3246 ;// CONCATENATED MODULE: ../node_modules/@rjsf/utils/lib/orderProperties.js
3247 /** Given a list of `properties` and an `order` list, returns a list that contains the `properties` ordered correctly.
3248  * If `order` is not an array, then the untouched `properties` list is returned. Otherwise `properties` is ordered per
3249  * the `order` list. If `order` contains a '*' then any `properties` that are not mentioned explicity in `order` will be
3250  * places in the location of the `*`.
3251  *
3252  * @param properties - The list of property keys to be ordered
3253  * @param order - An array of property keys to be ordered first, with an optional '*' property
3254  * @returns - A list with the `properties` ordered
3255  * @throws - Error when the properties cannot be ordered correctly
3256  */
3257 function orderProperties(properties, order) {
3258     if (!Array.isArray(order)) {
3259         return properties;
3260     }
3261     const arrayToHash = (arr) => arr.reduce((prev, curr) => {
3262         prev[curr] = true;
3263         return prev;
3264     }, {});
3265     const errorPropList = (arr) => arr.length > 1 ? `properties '${arr.join("', '")}'` : `property '${arr[0]}'`;
3266     const propertyHash = arrayToHash(properties);
3267     const orderFiltered = order.filter((prop) => prop === '*' || propertyHash[prop]);
3268     const orderHash = arrayToHash(orderFiltered);
3269     const rest = properties.filter((prop) => !orderHash[prop]);
3270     const restIndex = orderFiltered.indexOf('*');
3271     if (restIndex === -1) {
3272         if (rest.length) {
3273             throw new Error(`uiSchema order list does not contain ${errorPropList(rest)}`);
3274         }
3275         return orderFiltered;
3276     }
3277     if (restIndex !== orderFiltered.lastIndexOf('*')) {
3278         throw new Error('uiSchema order list contains more than one wildcard item');
3279     }
3280     const complete = [...orderFiltered];
3281     complete.splice(restIndex, 1, ...rest);
3282     return complete;
3283 }

3301 /** Parses the `dateString` into a `DateObject`, including the time information when `includeTime` is true
3302  *
3303  * @param dateString - The date string to parse into a DateObject
3304  * @param [includeTime=true] - Optional flag, if false, will not include the time data into the object
3305  * @returns - The date string converted to a `DateObject`
3306  * @throws - Error when the date cannot be parsed from the string
3307  */
3308 function parseDateString(dateString, includeTime = true) {
3309     if (!dateString) {
3310         return {
3311             year: -1,
3312             month: -1,
3313             day: -1,
3314             hour: includeTime ? -1 : 0,
3315             minute: includeTime ? -1 : 0,
3316             second: includeTime ? -1 : 0,
3317         };
3318     }
3319     const date = new Date(dateString);
3320     if (Number.isNaN(date.getTime())) {
3321         throw new Error('Unable to parse date ' + dateString);

3323     return {
3324         year: date.getUTCFullYear(),
3325         month: date.getUTCMonth() + 1,
3326         day: date.getUTCDate(),
3327         hour: includeTime ? date.getUTCHours() : 0,
3328         minute: includeTime ? date.getUTCMinutes() : 0,
3329         second: includeTime ? date.getUTCSeconds() : 0,
3330     };
3331 }

3333 ;// CONCATENATED MODULE: ../node_modules/@rjsf/utils/lib/schemaRequiresTrueValue.js
3334 /** Check to see if a `schema` specifies that a value must be true. This happens when:
3335  * - `schema.const` is truthy
3336  * - `schema.enum` == `[true]`
3337  * - `schema.anyOf` or `schema.oneOf` has a single value which recursively returns true
3338  * - `schema.allOf` has at least one value which recursively returns true
3339  *
3340  * @param schema - The schema to check
3341  * @returns - True if the schema specifies a value that must be true, false otherwise
3342  */
3343 function schemaRequiresTrueValue(schema) {
3344     // Check if const is a truthy value
3345     if (schema.const) {
3346         return true;
3347     }
3348     // Check if an enum has a single value of true
3349     if (schema.enum && schema.enum.length === 1 && schema.enum[0] === true) {
3350         return true;
3351     }
3352     // If anyOf has a single value, evaluate the subschema
3353     if (schema.anyOf && schema.anyOf.length === 1) {
3354         return schemaRequiresTrueValue(schema.anyOf[0]);
3355     }
3356     // If oneOf has a single value, evaluate the subschema
3357     if (schema.oneOf && schema.oneOf.length === 1) {
3358         return schemaRequiresTrueValue(schema.oneOf[0]);
3359     }
3360     // Evaluate each subschema in allOf, to see if one of them requires a true value
3361     if (schema.allOf) {
3362         const schemaSome = (subSchema) => schemaRequiresTrueValue(subSchema);
3363         return schema.allOf.some(schemaSome);
3364     }
3365     return false;
3366 }

3401 /** Converts an `errorSchema` into a list of `RJSFValidationErrors`
3402  *
3403  * @param errorSchema - The `ErrorSchema` instance to convert
3404  * @param [fieldPath=[]] - The current field path, defaults to [] if not specified
3405  * @returns - The list of `RJSFValidationErrors` extracted from the `errorSchema`
3406  */
3407 function toErrorList(errorSchema, fieldPath = []) {
3408     if (!errorSchema) {
3409         return [];
3410     }
3411     let errorList = [];
3412     if (ERRORS_KEY in errorSchema) {
3413         errorList = errorList.concat(errorSchema[ERRORS_KEY].map((message) => {
3414             const property = `.${fieldPath.join('.')}`;
3415             return {
3416                 property,
3417                 message,
3418                 stack: `${property} ${message}`,
3419             };
3420         }));
3421     }
3422     return Object.keys(errorSchema).reduce((acc, key) => {
3423         if (key !== ERRORS_KEY) {
3424             const childSchema = errorSchema[key];
3425             if (isPlainObject_default()(childSchema)) {
3426                 acc = acc.concat(toErrorList(childSchema, [...fieldPath, key]));
3427             }
3428         }
3429         return acc;
3430     }, errorList);
3431 }

3443  *   {property: '.level1.level2[4].level3', message: 'err b'},
3444  * ]
3445  * Into an error tree:
3446  * {
3447  *   level1: {
3448  *     level2: {
3449  *       2: {level3: {errors: ['err a', 'err b']}},
3450  *       4: {level3: {errors: ['err b']}},
3451  *     }
3452  *   }
3453  * };
3454  *
3455  * @param errors - The list of RJSFValidationError objects
3456  * @returns - The `ErrorSchema` built from the list of `RJSFValidationErrors`
3457  */
3458 function toErrorSchema(errors) {
3459     const builder = new ErrorSchemaBuilder();
3460     if (errors.length) {
3461         errors.forEach((error) => {
3462             const { property, message } = error;
3463             // When the property is the root element, just use an empty array for the path
3464             const path = property === '.' ? [] : toPath_default()(property);
3465             // If the property is at the root (.level1) then toPath creates
3466             // an empty array element at the first index. Remove it.
3467             if (path.length > 0 && path[0] === '') {
3468                 path.splice(0, 1);
3469             }
3470             if (message) {
3471                 builder.addErrors(message, path);
3472             }
3473         });
3474     }
3475     return builder.ErrorSchema;
3476 }

3480 /** Unwraps the `errorHandler` structure into the associated `ErrorSchema`, stripping the `addError()` functions from it
3481  *
3482  * @param errorHandler - The `FormValidation` error handling structure
3483  * @returns - The `ErrorSchema` resulting from the stripping of the `addError()` function
3484  */
3485 function unwrapErrorHandler(errorHandler) {
3486     return Object.keys(errorHandler).reduce((acc, key) => {
3487         if (key === 'addError') {
3488             return acc;
3489         }
3490         else {
3491             const childSchema = errorHandler[key];
3492             if (isPlainObject_default()(childSchema)) {
3493                 return {
3494                     ...acc,
3495                     [key]: unwrapErrorHandler(childSchema),
3496                 };
3497             }
3498             return { ...acc, [key]: childSchema };
3499         }
3500     }, {});
3501 }

3504 
3505 /** Converts a UTC date string into a local Date format
3506  *
3507  * @param jsonDate - A UTC date string
3508  * @returns - An empty string when `jsonDate` is falsey, otherwise a date string in local format
3509  */
3510 function utcToLocal(jsonDate) {
3511     if (!jsonDate) {
3512         return '';
3513     }
3514     // required format of `'yyyy-MM-ddThh:mm' followed by optional ':ss' or ':ss.SSS'
3515     // https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/input.html#local-date-and-time-state-(type%3Ddatetime-local)
3516     // > should be a _valid local date and time string_ (not GMT)
3517     // Note - date constructor passed local ISO-8601 does not correctly
3518     // change time to UTC in node pre-8
3519     const date = new Date(jsonDate);
3520     const yyyy = pad(date.getFullYear(), 4);
3521     const MM = pad(date.getMonth() + 1, 2);
3522     const dd = pad(date.getDate(), 2);
3523     const hh = pad(date.getHours(), 2);
3524     const mm = pad(date.getMinutes(), 2);
3525     const ss = pad(date.getSeconds(), 2);
3526     const SSS = pad(date.getMilliseconds(), 3);
3527     return `${yyyy}-${MM}-${dd}T${hh}:${mm}:${ss}.${SSS}`;
3528 }

3534 /** Merges the errors in `additionalErrorSchema` into the existing `validationData` by combining the hierarchies in the
3535  * two `ErrorSchema`s and then appending the error list from the `additionalErrorSchema` obtained by calling
3536  * `toErrorList()` on the `errors` in the `validationData`. If no `additionalErrorSchema` is passed, then
3537  * `validationData` is returned.
3538  *
3539  * @param validationData - The current `ValidationData` into which to merge the additional errors
3540  * @param [additionalErrorSchema] - The optional additional set of errors in an `ErrorSchema`
3541  * @returns - The `validationData` with the additional errors from `additionalErrorSchema` merged into it, if provided.
3542  */
3543 function validationDataMerge(validationData, additionalErrorSchema) {
3544     if (!additionalErrorSchema) {
3545         return validationData;
3546     }
3547     const { errors: oldErrors, errorSchema: oldErrorSchema } = validationData;
3548     let errors = toErrorList(additionalErrorSchema);
3549     let errorSchema = additionalErrorSchema;
3550     if (!isEmpty_default()(oldErrorSchema)) {
3551         errorSchema = mergeObjects(oldErrorSchema, additionalErrorSchema, true);
3552         errors = [...oldErrors].concat(errors);
3553     }
3554     return { errorSchema, errors };
3555 }

3560 /** Takes a `node` object and transforms any contained `$ref` node variables with a prefix, recursively calling
3561  * `withIdRefPrefix` for any other elements.
3562  *
3563  * @param node - The object node to which a ROOT_SCHEMA_PREFIX is added when a REF_KEY is part of it
3564  */
3565 function withIdRefPrefixObject(node) {
3566     for (const key in node) {
3567         const realObj = node;
3568         const value = realObj[key];
3569         if (key === REF_KEY && typeof value === 'string' && value.startsWith('#')) {
3570             realObj[key] = ROOT_SCHEMA_PREFIX + value;
3571         }
3572         else {
3573             realObj[key] = withIdRefPrefix(value);
3574         }
3575     }
3576     return node;
3577 }
3578 /** Takes a `node` object list and transforms any contained `$ref` node variables with a prefix, recursively calling
3579  * `withIdRefPrefix` for any other elements.
3580  *
3581  * @param node - The list of object nodes to which a ROOT_SCHEMA_PREFIX is added when a REF_KEY is part of it
3582  */
3583 function withIdRefPrefixArray(node) {
3584     for (let i = 0; i < node.length; i++) {
3585         node[i] = withIdRefPrefix(node[i]);
3586     }
3587     return node;
3588 }
3589 /** Recursively prefixes all `$ref`s in a schema with the value of the `ROOT_SCHEMA_PREFIX` constant.
3590  * This is used in isValid to make references to the rootSchema
3591  *
3592  * @param schemaNode - The object node to which a ROOT_SCHEMA_PREFIX is added when a REF_KEY is part of it
3593  * @returns - A copy of the `schemaNode` with updated `$ref`s
3594  */
3595 function withIdRefPrefix(schemaNode) {
3596     if (Array.isArray(schemaNode)) {
3597         return withIdRefPrefixArray([...schemaNode]);
3598     }
3599     if (isObject_default()(schemaNode)) {
3600         return withIdRefPrefixObject({ ...schemaNode });
3601     }
3602     return schemaNode;
3603 }

3690 /** An implementation of the `ValidatorType` interface that is designed for use in capturing schemas used by the
3691  * `isValid()` function. The rest of the implementation of the interface throws errors when it is attempted to be used.
3692  * An instance of the object allows the caller to capture the schemas used in calls to the `isValid()` function. These
3693  * captured schema, along with the root schema used to construct the object are stored in the map of schemas keyed by
3694  * the hashed value of the schema. NOTE: After hashing the schema, an $id with the hash value is added to the
3695  * schema IF that schema doesn't already have an $id, prior to putting the schema into the map.
3696  */
3697 class ParserValidator {
3698     /** Construct the ParserValidator for the given `rootSchema`. This `rootSchema` will be stashed in the `schemaMap`
3699      * first.
3700      *
3701      * @param rootSchema - The root schema against which this validator will be executed
3702      */
3703     constructor(rootSchema) {
3704         /** The map of schemas encountered by the ParserValidator */
3705         this.schemaMap = {};
3706         this.rootSchema = rootSchema;
3707         this.addSchema(rootSchema, hashForSchema(rootSchema));
3708     }
3709     /** Adds the given `schema` to the `schemaMap` keyed by the `hash` or `ID_KEY` if present on the `schema`. If the
3710      * schema does not have an `ID_KEY`, then the `hash` will be added as the `ID_KEY` to allow the schema to be
3711      * associated with it's `hash` for future use (by a schema compiler).
3712      *
3713      * @param schema - The schema which is to be added to the map
3714      * @param hash - The hash value at which to map the schema
3715      */
3716     addSchema(schema, hash) {
3717         const key = get_default()(schema, ID_KEY, hash);
3718         const identifiedSchema = { ...schema, [ID_KEY]: key };
3719         const existing = this.schemaMap[key];
3720         if (!existing) {
3721             this.schemaMap[key] = identifiedSchema;
3722         }
3723         else if (!isEqual_default()(existing, identifiedSchema)) {
3724             console.error('existing schema:', JSON.stringify(existing, null, 2));
3725             console.error('new schema:', JSON.stringify(identifiedSchema, null, 2));
3726             throw new Error(`Two different schemas exist with the same key ${key}! What a bad coincidence. If possible, try adding an $id to one of the schemas`);
3727         }
3728     }
3729     /** Returns the current `schemaMap` to the caller
3730      */
3731     getSchemaMap() {
3732         return this.schemaMap;
3733     }
3734     /** Implements the `ValidatorType` `isValid()` method to capture the `schema` in the `schemaMap`. Throws an error when
3735      * the `rootSchema` is not the same as the root schema provided during construction.
3736      *
3737      * @param schema - The schema to record in the `schemaMap`
3738      * @param _formData - The formData parameter that is ignored
3739      * @param rootSchema - The root schema associated with the schema
3740      * @throws - Error when the given `rootSchema` differs from the root schema provided during construction
3741      */
3742     isValid(schema, _formData, rootSchema) {
3743         if (!isEqual_default()(rootSchema, this.rootSchema)) {
3744             throw new Error('Unexpectedly calling isValid() with a rootSchema that differs from the construction rootSchema');
3745         }
3746         this.addSchema(schema, hashForSchema(schema));
3747         return false;
3748     }
3749     /** Implements the `ValidatorType` `rawValidation()` method to throw an error since it is never supposed to be called
3750      *
3751      * @param _schema - The schema parameter that is ignored
3752      * @param _formData - The formData parameter that is ignored
3753      */
3754     rawValidation(_schema, _formData) {
3755         throw new Error('Unexpectedly calling the `rawValidation()` method during schema parsing');
3756     }
3757     /** Implements the `ValidatorType` `toErrorList()` method to throw an error since it is never supposed to be called
3758      *
3759      * @param _errorSchema - The error schema parameter that is ignored
3760      * @param _fieldPath - The field path parameter that is ignored
3761      */
3762     toErrorList(_errorSchema, _fieldPath) {
3763         throw new Error('Unexpectedly calling the `toErrorList()` method during schema parsing');
3764     }
3765     /** Implements the `ValidatorType` `validateFormData()` method to throw an error since it is never supposed to be
3766      * called
3767      *
3768      * @param _formData - The formData parameter that is ignored

3770      * @param _customValidate - The customValidate parameter that is ignored
3771      * @param _transformErrors - The transformErrors parameter that is ignored
3772      * @param _uiSchema - The uiSchema parameter that is ignored
3773      */
3774     validateFormData(_formData, _schema, _customValidate, _transformErrors, _uiSchema) {
3775         throw new Error('Unexpectedly calling the `validateFormData()` method during schema parsing');
3776     }
3777 }

3785 /** Recursive function used to parse the given `schema` belonging to the `rootSchema`. The `validator` is used to
3786  * capture the sub-schemas that the `isValid()` function is called with. For each schema returned by the
3787  * `retrieveSchemaInternal()`, the `resolveAnyOrOneOfSchemas()` function is called. For each of the schemas returned
3788  * from THAT call have `properties`, then each of the sub-schema property objects are then recursively parsed.
3789  *
3790  * @param validator - The `ParserValidator` implementation used to capture `isValid()` calls during parsing
3791  * @param recurseList - The list of schemas returned from the `retrieveSchemaInternal`, preventing infinite recursion
3792  * @param rootSchema - The root schema from which the schema parsing began
3793  * @param schema - The current schema element being parsed
3794  */
3795 function parseSchema(validator, recurseList, rootSchema, schema) {
3796     const schemas = retrieveSchemaInternal(validator, schema, rootSchema, undefined, true);
3797     schemas.forEach((schema) => {
3798         const sameSchemaIndex = recurseList.findIndex((item) => isEqual_default()(item, schema));
3799         if (sameSchemaIndex === -1) {
3800             recurseList.push(schema);
3801             const allOptions = resolveAnyOrOneOfSchemas(validator, schema, rootSchema, true);
3802             allOptions.forEach((s) => {
3803                 if (PROPERTIES_KEY in s && s[PROPERTIES_KEY]) {
3804                     forEach_default()(schema[PROPERTIES_KEY], (value) => {
3805                         parseSchema(validator, recurseList, rootSchema, value);
3806                     });
3807                 }
3808             });
3809             if (ITEMS_KEY in schema && !Array.isArray(schema.items) && typeof schema.items !== 'boolean') {
3810                 parseSchema(validator, recurseList, rootSchema, schema.items);
3811             }
3812         }
3813     });
3814 }
3815 /** Parses the given `rootSchema` to extract out all the sub-schemas that maybe contained within it. Returns a map of
3816  * the hash of the schema to schema/sub-schema.
3817  *
3818  * @param rootSchema - The root schema to parse for sub-schemas used by `isValid()` calls
3819  * @returns - The `SchemaMap` of all schemas that were parsed
3820  */
3821 function schemaParser(rootSchema) {
3822     const validator = new ParserValidator(rootSchema);
3823     const recurseList = [];
3824     parseSchema(validator, recurseList, rootSchema, rootSchema);
3825     return validator.getSchemaMap();
3826 }

3916 /**
3917 * FUNCTION: gcd( a, b )
3918 *	Computes the greatest common divisor of two integers `a` and `b`, using the binary GCD algorithm.
3919 *
3920 * @param {Number} a - integer
3921 * @param {Number} b - integer
3922 * @returns {Number} greatest common divisor
3923 */
3924 function gcd( a, b ) {
3925 	var k = 1,
3926 		t;
3927 	// Simple cases:
3928 	if ( a === 0 ) {
3929 		return b;
3930 	}
3931 	if ( b === 0 ) {
3932 		return a;
3933 	}
3934 	// Reduce `a` and/or `b` to odd numbers and keep track of the greatest power of 2 dividing both `a` and `b`...
3935 	while ( a%2 === 0 && b%2 === 0 ) {
3936 		a = a / 2; // right shift
3937 		b = b / 2; // right shift
3938 		k = k * 2; // left shift
3939 	}
3940 	// Reduce `a` to an odd number...
3941 	while ( a%2 === 0 ) {
3942 		a = a / 2; // right shift
3943 	}
3944 	// Henceforth, `a` is always odd...
3945 	while ( b ) {
3946 		// Remove all factors of 2 in `b`, as they are not common...
3947 		while ( b%2 === 0 ) {
3948 			b = b / 2; // right shift
3949 		}
3950 		// `a` and `b` are both odd. Swap values such that `b` is the larger of the two values, and then set `b` to the difference (which is even)...
3951 		if ( a > b ) {
3952 			t = b;
3953 			b = a;
3954 			a = t;
3955 		}
3956 		b = b - a; // b=0 iff b=a
3957 	}
3958 	// Restore common factors of 2...
3959 	return k * a;
3960 } // end FUNCTION gcd()
3961 
3962 /**
3963 * FUNCTION: bitwise( a, b )
3964 *	Computes the greatest common divisor of two integers `a` and `b`, using the binary GCD algorithm and bitwise operations.
3965 *
3966 * @param {Number} a - safe integer
3967 * @param {Number} b - safe integer
3968 * @returns {Number} greatest common divisor
3969 */
3970 function bitwise( a, b ) {
3971 	var k = 0,
3972 		t;
3973 	// Simple cases:
3974 	if ( a === 0 ) {
3975 		return b;
3976 	}
3977 	if ( b === 0 ) {
3978 		return a;
3979 	}
3980 	// Reduce `a` and/or `b` to odd numbers and keep track of the greatest power of 2 dividing both `a` and `b`...
3981 	while ( (a & 1) === 0 && (b & 1) === 0 ) {
3982 		a >>>= 1; // right shift
3983 		b >>>= 1; // right shift
3984 		k++;
3985 	}
3986 	// Reduce `a` to an odd number...
3987 	while ( (a & 1) === 0 ) {
3988 		a >>>= 1; // right shift
3989 	}
3990 	// Henceforth, `a` is always odd...
3991 	while ( b ) {
3992 		// Remove all factors of 2 in `b`, as they are not common...
3993 		while ( (b & 1) === 0 ) {
3994 			b >>>= 1; // right shift
3995 		}
3996 		// `a` and `b` are both odd. Swap values such that `b` is the larger of the two values, and then set `b` to the difference (which is even)...
3997 		if ( a > b ) {
3998 			t = b;
3999 			b = a;
4000 			a = t;
4001 		}
4002 		b = b - a; // b=0 iff b=a
4003 	}
4004 	// Restore common factors of 2...
4005 	return a << k;
4006 } // end FUNCTION bitwise()
4007 
4008 
4009 // GREATEST COMMON DIVISOR //
4010 
4011 /**
4012 * FUNCTION: compute( arr[, clbk] )
4013 *	Computes the greatest common divisor.
4014 *
4015 * @param {Number[]|Number} arr - input array of integers
4016 * @param {Function|Number} [clbk] - accessor function for accessing array values
4017 * @returns {Number|Null} greatest common divisor or null
4018 */
4019 function compute() {
4020 	var nargs = arguments.length,
4021 		args,
4022 		clbk,
4023 		arr,
4024 		len,
4025 		a, b,
4026 		i;
4027 
4028 	// Copy the input arguments to an array...
4029 	args = new Array( nargs );
4030 	for ( i = 0; i < nargs; i++ ) {
4031 		args[ i ] = arguments[ i ];
4032 	}
4033 	// Have we been provided with integer arguments?
4034 	if ( isIntegerArray( args ) ) {
4035 		if ( nargs === 2 ) {
4036 			a = args[ 0 ];
4037 			b = args[ 1 ];
4038 			if ( a < 0 ) {
4039 				a = -a;
4040 			}
4041 			if ( b < 0 ) {
4042 				b = -b;
4043 			}
4044 			if ( a <= MAXINT && b <= MAXINT ) {
4045 				return bitwise( a, b );
4046 			} else {
4047 				return gcd( a, b );
4048 			}
4049 		}
4050 		arr = args;
4051 	}
4052 	// If not integers, ensure the first argument is an array...
4053 	else if ( !isArray( args[ 0 ] ) ) {
4054 		throw new TypeError( 'gcd()::invalid input argument. Must provide an array of integers. Value: `' + args[ 0 ] + '`.' );
4055 	}
4056 	// Have we been provided with more than one argument? If so, ensure that the accessor argument is a function...
4057 	else if ( nargs > 1 ) {
4058 		arr = args[ 0 ];
4059 		clbk = args[ 1 ];
4060 		if ( !isFunction( clbk ) ) {
4061 			throw new TypeError( 'gcd()::invalid input argument. Accessor must be a function. Value: `' + clbk + '`.' );
4062 		}
4063 	}
4064 	// We have been provided an array...
4065 	else {
4066 		arr = args[ 0 ];
4067 	}
4068 	len = arr.length;
4069 
4070 	// Check if a sufficient number of values have been provided...
4071 	if ( len < 2 ) {
4072 		return null;
4073 	}
4074 	// If an accessor is provided, extract the array values...
4075 	if ( clbk ) {
4076 		a = new Array( len );
4077 		for ( i = 0; i < len; i++ ) {
4078 			a[ i ] = clbk( arr[ i ], i );
4079 		}
4080 		arr = a;
4081 	}
4082 	// Given an input array, ensure all array values are integers...
4083 	if ( nargs < 3 ) {
4084 		if ( !isIntegerArray( arr ) ) {
4085 			throw new TypeError( 'gcd()::invalid input argument. Accessed array values must be integers. Value: `' + arr + '`.' );
4086 		}
4087 	}
4088 	// Convert any negative integers to positive integers...
4089 	for ( i = 0; i < len; i++ ) {
4090 		a = arr[ i ];
4091 		if ( a < 0 ) {
4092 			arr[ i ] = -a;
4093 		}
4094 	}
4095 	// Exploit the fact that the gcd is an associative function...
4096 	a = arr[ 0 ];
4097 	for ( i = 1; i < len; i++ ) {
4098 		b = arr[ i ];
4099 		if ( b <= MAXINT && a <= MAXINT ) {
4100 			a = bitwise( a, b );
4101 		} else {
4102 			a = gcd( a, b );
4103 		}
4104 	}
4105 	return a;
4106 } // end FUNCTION compute()

4132 /**
4133 * FUNCTION: lcm( arr[, clbk] )
4134 *	Computes the least common multiple (lcm).
4135 *
4136 * @param {Number[]|Number} arr - input array of integers
4137 * @param {Function|Number} [accessor] - accessor function for accessing array values
4138 * @returns {Number|Null} least common multiple or null
4139 */
4140 function lcm() {
4141 	var nargs = arguments.length,
4142 		args,
4143 		clbk,
4144 		arr,
4145 		len,
4146 		a, b,
4147 		i;
4148 
4149 	// Copy the input arguments to an array...
4150 	args = new Array( nargs );
4151 	for ( i = 0; i < nargs; i++ ) {

4153 	}
4154 	// Have we been provided with integer arguments?
4155 	if ( isIntegerArray( args ) ) {
4156 		if ( nargs === 2 ) {
4157 			a = args[ 0 ];
4158 			b = args[ 1 ];
4159 			if ( a < 0 ) {
4160 				a = -a;
4161 			}
4162 			if ( b < 0 ) {
4163 				b = -b;
4164 			}
4165 			if ( a === 0 || b === 0 ) {
4166 				return 0;
4167 			}
4168 			return ( a/gcd(a,b) ) * b;
4169 		}

4171 	}

4175 	}
4176 	// Have we been provided with more than one argument? If so, ensure that the accessor argument is a function...
4177 	else if ( nargs > 1 ) {
4178 		arr = args[ 0 ];
4179 		clbk = args[ 1 ];
4180 		if ( !isFunction( clbk ) ) {
4181 			throw new TypeError( 'lcm()::invalid input argument. Accessor must be a function. Value: `' + clbk + '`.' );
4182 		}
4183 	}
4184 	// We have been provided an array...
4185 	else {
4186 		arr = args[ 0 ];
4187 	}
4188 	len = arr.length;
4189 
4190 	// Check if a sufficient number of values have been provided...
4191 	if ( len < 2 ) {
4192 		return null;
4193 	}
4194 	// If an accessor is provided, extract the array values...
4195 	if ( clbk ) {
4196 		a = new Array( len );
4197 		for ( i = 0; i < len; i++ ) {
4198 			a[ i ] = clbk( arr[ i ], i );
4199 		}
4200 		arr = a;
4201 	}
4202 	// Given an input array, ensure all array values are integers...
4203 	if ( nargs < 3 ) {
4204 		if ( !isIntegerArray( arr ) ) {
4205 			throw new TypeError( 'lcm()::invalid input argument. Accessed array values must be integers. Value: `' + arr + '`.' );
4206 		}
4207 	}

4209 	for ( i = 0; i < len; i++ ) {
4210 		a = arr[ i ];
4211 		if ( a < 0 ) {
4212 			arr[ i ] = -a;
4213 		}
4214 	}
4215 	// Exploit the fact that the lcm is an associative function...
4216 	a = arr[ 0 ];
4217 	for ( i = 1; i < len; i++ ) {

4347 function compare(a, b, options) {

4350   })
4351

4353     return true
4354   }
4355 
4356   if (!isSchema(a) || !isSchema(b)) {
4357     throw new Error('Either of the values are not a JSON schema.')
4358   }
4359   if (a === b) {
4360     return true
4361   }
4362 
4363   if (isBoolean(a) && isBoolean(b)) {
4364     return a === b
4365   }
4366 
4367   if ((a === undefined && b === false) || (b === undefined && a === false)) {
4368     return false

4378     allKeys = allKeys.filter(k => options.ignore.indexOf(k) === -1)
4379   }
4380 
4381   if (!allKeys.length) {
4382     return true
4383   }

4386     return compare(a, b, options)
4387   }

4391     var bValue = b[key]

4394       return compare(aValue, bValue, options)

4408       if ((!has(a, key) && has(b, key)) || (has(a, key) && !has(b, key))) {
4409         return aValue === bValue
4410       }
4411     }

4414     if (!isBoolean(result)) {
4415       throw new Error('Comparer must return true or false')
4416     }

4709   return function(a, b) {

4726 function tryMergeSchemaGroups(schemaGroups, mergeSchemas) {
4727   return schemaGroups.map(function(schemas, index) {
4728     try {
4729       return mergeSchemas(schemas, index)
4730     } catch (e) {
4731       return undefined
4732     }
4733   }).filter(notUndefined)

4736 function keys(obj) {
4737   if (isPlainObject(obj) || Array.isArray(obj)) {
4738     return Object.keys(obj)
4739   } else {
4740     return []

4744 function getAnyOfCombinations(arrOfArrays, combinations) {
4745   combinations = combinations || []
4746   if (!arrOfArrays.length) {
4747     return combinations
4748   }
4749 
4750   const values = arrOfArrays.slice(0).shift()
4751   const rest = arrOfArrays.slice(1)
4752   if (combinations.length) {
4753     return getAnyOfCombinations(rest, flatten(combinations.map(combination => values.map(item => ([item].concat(combination))))))
4754   }
4755   return getAnyOfCombinations(rest, values.map(item => (item)))
4756 }

4758 function throwIncompatible(values, paths) {
4759   let asJSON
4760   try {
4761     asJSON = values.map(function(val) {
4762       return JSON.stringify(val, null, 2)
4763     }).join('\n')
4764   } catch (variable) {
4765     asJSON = values.join(', ')
4766   }
4767   throw new Error('Could not resolve values for path:"' + paths.join('.') + '". They are probably incompatible. Values: \n' + asJSON)
4768 }

4770 function callGroupResolver(complexKeywords, resolverName, schemas, mergeSchemas, options, parents) {
4771   if (complexKeywords.length) {
4772     const resolverConfig = options.complexResolvers[resolverName]
4773     if (!resolverConfig || !resolverConfig.resolver) {
4774       throw new Error('No resolver found for ' + resolverName)
4775     }
4776 
4777     // extract all keywords from all the schemas that have one or more
4778     // then remove all undefined ones and not unique
4779     const extractedKeywordsOnly = schemas.map(schema => complexKeywords.reduce((all, key) => {
4780       if (schema[key] !== undefined) all[key] = schema[key]
4781       return all
4782     }, {}))
4783     const unique = uniqWith(extractedKeywordsOnly, compare)
4784 
4785     // create mergers that automatically add the path of the keyword for use in the complex resolver
4786     const mergers = resolverConfig.keywords.reduce((all, key) => ({
4787       ...all,
4788       [key]: (schemas, extraKey = []) => mergeSchemas(schemas, null, parents.concat(key, extraKey))
4789     }), {})
4790 
4791     const result = resolverConfig.resolver(unique, parents.concat(resolverName), mergers, options)
4792 
4793     if (!isPlainObject(result)) {
4794       throwIncompatible(unique, parents.concat(resolverName))
4795     }
4796 
4797     return result
4798   }
4799 }

4816 const defaultResolvers = {
4817   type(compacted) {
4818     if (compacted.some(Array.isArray)) {
4819       const normalized = compacted.map(function(val) {
4820         return Array.isArray(val)
4821           ? val
4822           : [val]
4823       })
4824       const common = intersection.apply(null, normalized)
4825 
4826       if (common.length === 1) {
4827         return common[0]
4828       } else if (common.length > 1) {
4829         return uniq(common)
4830       }
4831     }
4832   },
4833   dependencies(compacted, paths, mergeSchemas) {
4834     const allChildren = allUniqueKeys(compacted)
4835 
4836     return allChildren.reduce(function(all, childKey) {
4837       const childSchemas = getValues(compacted, childKey)
4838       let innerCompacted = uniqWith(childSchemas.filter(notUndefined), isEqual)
4839 
4840       // to support dependencies
4841       const innerArrays = innerCompacted.filter(Array.isArray)
4842 
4843       if (innerArrays.length) {
4844         if (innerArrays.length === innerCompacted.length) {
4845           all[childKey] = stringArray(innerCompacted)
4846         } else {
4847           const innerSchemas = innerCompacted.filter(isSchema)
4848           const arrayMetaScheams = innerArrays.map(createRequiredMetaArray)
4849           all[childKey] = mergeSchemas(innerSchemas.concat(arrayMetaScheams), childKey)
4850         }
4851         return all
4852       }
4853 
4854       innerCompacted = uniqWith(innerCompacted, compare)
4855 
4856       all[childKey] = mergeSchemas(innerCompacted, childKey)
4857       return all
4858     }, {})
4859   },
4860   oneOf(compacted, paths, mergeSchemas) {
4861     const combinations = getAnyOfCombinations(cloneDeep(compacted))
4862     const result = tryMergeSchemaGroups(combinations, mergeSchemas)
4863     const unique = uniqWith(result, compare)
4864 
4865     if (unique.length) {
4866       return unique
4867     }
4868   },
4869   not(compacted) {
4870     return { anyOf: compacted }
4871   },
4872   pattern(compacted) {
4873     return compacted.map(r => '(?=' + r + ')').join('')
4874   },
4875   multipleOf(compacted) {
4876     let integers = compacted.slice(0)
4877     let factor = 1
4878     while (integers.some(n => !Number.isInteger(n))) {
4879       integers = integers.map(n => n * 10)
4880       factor = factor * 10
4881     }
4882     return computeLcm(integers) / factor
4883   },
4884   enum(compacted) {
4885     const enums = intersectionWith.apply(null, compacted.concat(isEqual))
4886     if (enums.length) {
4887       return sortBy(enums)
4888     }
4889   }
4890 }

4898 defaultResolvers.contains = schemaResolver

4920 const defaultComplexResolvers = {
4921   properties: propertiesResolver,
4922   items: itemsResolver

4925 function merger(rootSchema, options, totalSchemas) {
4926   totalSchemas = totalSchemas || []
4927   options = defaultsDeep(options, {
4928     ignoreAdditionalProperties: false,
4929     resolvers: defaultResolvers,
4930     complexResolvers: defaultComplexResolvers,
4931     deep: true
4932   })
4933 
4934   const complexResolvers = Object.entries(options.complexResolvers)
4935 
4936   function mergeSchemas(schemas, base, parents) {
4937     schemas = cloneDeep(schemas.filter(notUndefined))
4938     parents = parents || []
4939     const merged = isPlainObject(base)
4940       ? base
4941       : {}
4942 
4943     // return undefined, an empty schema
4944     if (!schemas.length) {
4945       return
4946     }
4947 
4948     if (schemas.some(isFalse)) {
4949       return false
4950     }
4951 
4952     if (schemas.every(isTrue)) {
4953       return true
4954     }
4955 
4956     // there are no false and we don't need the true ones as they accept everything
4957     schemas = schemas.filter(isPlainObject)
4958 
4959     const allKeys = allUniqueKeys(schemas)
4960     if (options.deep && contains(allKeys, 'allOf')) {
4961       return merger({
4962         allOf: schemas
4963       }, options, totalSchemas)
4964     }
4965 
4966     const complexKeysArr = complexResolvers.map(([mainKeyWord, resolverConf]) =>
4967       allKeys.filter(k => resolverConf.keywords.includes(k)))
4968 
4969     // remove all complex keys before simple resolvers
4970     complexKeysArr.forEach(keys => pullAll(allKeys, keys))
4971 
4972     // call all simple resolvers for relevant keywords
4973     allKeys.forEach(function(key) {
4974       const values = getValues(schemas, key)
4975       const compacted = uniqWith(values.filter(notUndefined), compareProp(key))
4976 
4977       // arrayprops like anyOf and oneOf must be merged first, as they contains schemas
4978       // allOf is treated differently alltogether
4979       if (compacted.length === 1 && contains(schemaArrays, key)) {
4980         merged[key] = compacted[0].map(schema => mergeSchemas([schema], schema))
4981         // prop groups must always be resolved
4982       } else if (compacted.length === 1 && !contains(schemaGroupProps, key) && !contains(schemaProps, key)) {
4983         merged[key] = compacted[0]
4984       } else {
4985         const resolver = options.resolvers[key] || options.resolvers.defaultResolver
4986         if (!resolver) throw new Error('No resolver found for key ' + key + '. You can provide a resolver for this keyword in the options, or provide a default resolver.')
4987 
4988         const merger = (schemas, extraKey = []) => mergeSchemas(schemas, null, parents.concat(key, extraKey))
4989         merged[key] = resolver(compacted, parents.concat(key), merger, options)
4990 
4991         if (merged[key] === undefined) {
4992           throwIncompatible(compacted, parents.concat(key))
4993         } else if (merged[key] === undefined) {
4994           delete merged[key]
4995         }
4996       }
4997     })
4998 
4999     return complexResolvers.reduce((all, [resolverKeyword, config], index) => ({
5000       ...all,
5001       ...callGroupResolver(complexKeysArr[index], resolverKeyword, schemas, mergeSchemas, options, parents)
5002     }), merged)
5003   }
5004 
5005   const allSchemas = flattenDeep(getAllOf(rootSchema))
5006   const merged = mergeSchemas(allSchemas)
5007 
5008   return merged
5009 }
5010 
5011 merger.options = {
5012   resolvers: defaultResolvers
5013 }
5014 
5015 module.exports = merger

5023 var hasExcape = /~/
5024 var escapeMatcher = /~[01]/g
5025 function escapeReplacer (m) {
5026   switch (m) {
5027     case '~1': return '/'
5028     case '~0': return '~'
5029   }
5030   throw new Error('Invalid tilde escape: ' + m)
5031 }
5032 
5033 function untilde (str) {
5034   if (!hasExcape.test(str)) return str
5035   return str.replace(escapeMatcher, escapeReplacer)
5036 }

5038 function setter (obj, pointer, value) {
5039   var part
5040   var hasNextPart
5041 
5042   for (var p = 1, len = pointer.length; p < len;) {
5043     if (pointer[p] === 'constructor' || pointer[p] === 'prototype' || pointer[p] === '__proto__') return obj
5044 
5045     part = untilde(pointer[p++])
5046     hasNextPart = len > p
5047 
5048     if (typeof obj[part] === 'undefined') {
5049       // support setting of /-
5050       if (Array.isArray(obj) && part === '-') {
5051         part = obj.length
5052       }
5053 
5054       // support nested objects/array when setting values
5055       if (hasNextPart) {
5056         if ((pointer[p] !== '' && pointer[p] < Infinity) || pointer[p] === '-') obj[part] = []
5057         else obj[part] = {}
5058       }
5059     }
5060 
5061     if (!hasNextPart) break
5062     obj = obj[part]
5063   }
5064 
5065   var oldValue = obj[part]
5066   if (value === undefined) delete obj[part]
5067   else obj[part] = value
5068   return oldValue
5069 }
5070 
5071 function compilePointer (pointer) {
5072   if (typeof pointer === 'string') {
5073     pointer = pointer.split('/')
5074     if (pointer[0] === '') return pointer
5075     throw new Error('Invalid JSON pointer.')
5076   } else if (Array.isArray(pointer)) {
5077     for (const part of pointer) {
5078       if (typeof part !== 'string' && typeof part !== 'number') {
5079         throw new Error('Invalid JSON pointer. Must be of type string or number.')
5080       }
5081     }
5082     return pointer
5083   }
5084 
5085   throw new Error('Invalid JSON pointer.')
5086 }
5087 
5088 function get (obj, pointer) {
5089   if (typeof obj !== 'object') throw new Error('Invalid input object.')
5090   pointer = compilePointer(pointer)
5091   var len = pointer.length
5092   if (len === 1) return obj
5093 
5094   for (var p = 1; p < len;) {
5095     obj = obj[untilde(pointer[p++])]
5096     if (len === p) return obj
5097     if (typeof obj !== 'object' || obj === null) return undefined
5098   }
5099 }
5100 
5101 function set (obj, pointer, value) {
5102   if (typeof obj !== 'object') throw new Error('Invalid input object.')
5103   pointer = compilePointer(pointer)
5104   if (pointer.length === 0) throw new Error('Invalid JSON pointer for set.')
5105   return setter(obj, pointer, value)
5106 }
5107 
5108 function compile (pointer) {
5109   var compiled = compilePointer(pointer)
5110   return {
5111     get: function (object) {
5112       return get(object, compiled)
5113     },
5114     set: function (object, value) {
5115       return set(object, compiled, value)
5116     }
5117   }
5118 }

5120 exports.get = get
5121 exports.set = set
5122 exports.compile = compile

5307 var SetCache = __webpack_require__(52485),
5308     arrayIncludes = __webpack_require__(58095),
5309     arrayIncludesWith = __webpack_require__(21796),
5310     arrayMap = __webpack_require__(66070),
5311     baseUnary = __webpack_require__(39334),
5312     cacheHas = __webpack_require__(65581);
5313 
5314 /** Used as the size to enable large array optimizations. */
5315 var LARGE_ARRAY_SIZE = 200;
5316 
5317 /**
5318  * The base implementation of methods like `_.difference` without support
5319  * for excluding multiple arrays or iteratee shorthands.
5320  *
5321  * @private
5322  * @param {Array} array The array to inspect.
5323  * @param {Array} values The values to exclude.
5324  * @param {Function} [iteratee] The iteratee invoked per element.
5325  * @param {Function} [comparator] The comparator invoked per element.
5326  * @returns {Array} Returns the new array of filtered values.
5327  */
5328 function baseDifference(array, values, iteratee, comparator) {
5329   var index = -1,
5330       includes = arrayIncludes,
5331       isCommon = true,
5332       length = array.length,
5333       result = [],
5334       valuesLength = values.length;
5335 
5336   if (!length) {
5337     return result;
5338   }
5339   if (iteratee) {
5340     values = arrayMap(values, baseUnary(iteratee));
5341   }
5342   if (comparator) {
5343     includes = arrayIncludesWith;
5344     isCommon = false;
5345   }
5346   else if (values.length >= LARGE_ARRAY_SIZE) {
5347     includes = cacheHas;
5348     isCommon = false;
5349     values = new SetCache(values);
5350   }
5351   outer:
5352   while (++index < length) {
5353     var value = array[index],
5354         computed = iteratee == null ? value : iteratee(value);
5355 
5356     value = (comparator || value !== 0) ? value : 0;
5357     if (isCommon && computed === computed) {
5358       var valuesIndex = valuesLength;
5359       while (valuesIndex--) {
5360         if (values[valuesIndex] === computed) {
5361           continue outer;
5362         }
5363       }
5364       result.push(value);
5365     }
5366     else if (!includes(values, computed, comparator)) {
5367       result.push(value);
5368     }
5369   }
5370   return result;
5371 }
5372 
5373 module.exports = baseDifference;

5541     cacheHas = __webpack_require__(65581);
5542 
5543 /* Built-in method references for those with the same name as other `lodash` methods. */
5544 var nativeMin = Math.min;
5545 
5546 /**
5547  * The base implementation of methods like `_.intersection`, without support
5548  * for iteratee shorthands, that accepts an array of arrays to inspect.
5549  *
5550  * @private
5551  * @param {Array} arrays The arrays to inspect.
5552  * @param {Function} [iteratee] The iteratee invoked per element.
5553  * @param {Function} [comparator] The comparator invoked per element.
5554  * @returns {Array} Returns the new array of shared values.
5555  */
5556 function baseIntersection(arrays, iteratee, comparator) {
5557   var includes = comparator ? arrayIncludesWith : arrayIncludes,
5558       length = arrays[0].length,
5559       othLength = arrays.length,
5560       othIndex = othLength,
5561       caches = Array(othLength),
5562       maxLength = Infinity,
5563       result = [];
5564 
5565   while (othIndex--) {
5566     var array = arrays[othIndex];
5567     if (othIndex && iteratee) {
5568       array = arrayMap(array, baseUnary(iteratee));
5569     }
5570     maxLength = nativeMin(array.length, maxLength);
5571     caches[othIndex] = !comparator && (iteratee || (length >= 120 && array.length >= 120))
5572       ? new SetCache(othIndex && array)
5573       : undefined;
5574   }
5575   array = arrays[0];
5576 
5577   var index = -1,
5578       seen = caches[0];
5579 
5580   outer:
5581   while (++index < length && result.length < maxLength) {
5582     var value = array[index],
5583         computed = iteratee ? iteratee(value) : value;
5584 
5585     value = (comparator || value !== 0) ? value : 0;
5586     if (!(seen
5587           ? cacheHas(seen, computed)
5588           : includes(result, computed, comparator)
5589         )) {
5590       othIndex = othLength;
5591       while (--othIndex) {
5592         var cache = caches[othIndex];
5593         if (!(cache
5594               ? cacheHas(cache, computed)
5595               : includes(arrays[othIndex], computed, comparator))
5596             ) {
5597           continue outer;
5598         }
5599       }
5600       if (seen) {
5601         seen.push(computed);
5602       }
5603       result.push(value);
5604     }
5605   }
5606   return result;
5607 }

5622  * and tracks traversed objects.
5623  *
5624  * @private
5625  * @param {*} value The value to compare.
5626  * @param {*} other The other value to compare.
5627  * @param {boolean} bitmask The bitmask flags.
5628  *  1 - Unordered comparison
5629  *  2 - Partial comparison
5630  * @param {Function} [customizer] The function to customize comparisons.
5631  * @param {Object} [stack] Tracks traversed `value` and `other` objects.
5632  * @returns {boolean} Returns `true` if the values are equivalent, else `false`.
5633  */
5634 function baseIsEqual(value, other, bitmask, customizer, stack) {
5635   if (value === other) {
5636     return true;
5637   }
5638   if (value == null || other == null || (!isObjectLike(value) && !isObjectLike(other))) {
5639     return value !== value && other !== other;
5640   }

5654     equalByTag = __webpack_require__(370),

5656     getTag = __webpack_require__(3533),
5657     isArray = __webpack_require__(19785),
5658     isBuffer = __webpack_require__(43854),
5659     isTypedArray = __webpack_require__(48519);
5660 
5661 /** Used to compose bitmasks for value comparisons. */
5662 var COMPARE_PARTIAL_FLAG = 1;
5663 
5664 /** `Object#toString` result references. */
5665 var argsTag = '[object Arguments]',
5666     arrayTag = '[object Array]',
5667     objectTag = '[object Object]';
5668 
5669 /** Used for built-in method references. */
5670 var objectProto = Object.prototype;
5671 
5672 /** Used to check objects for own properties. */
5673 var hasOwnProperty = objectProto.hasOwnProperty;
5674 
5675 /**
5676  * A specialized version of `baseIsEqual` for arrays and objects which performs
5677  * deep comparisons and tracks traversed objects enabling objects with circular
5678  * references to be compared.
5679  *
5680  * @private
5681  * @param {Object} object The object to compare.
5682  * @param {Object} other The other object to compare.
5683  * @param {number} bitmask The bitmask flags. See `baseIsEqual` for more details.
5684  * @param {Function} customizer The function to customize comparisons.
5685  * @param {Function} equalFunc The function to determine equivalents of values.
5686  * @param {Object} [stack] Tracks traversed `object` and `other` objects.
5687  * @returns {boolean} Returns `true` if the objects are equivalent, else `false`.
5688  */
5689 function baseIsEqualDeep(object, other, bitmask, customizer, equalFunc, stack) {
5690   var objIsArr = isArray(object),
5691       othIsArr = isArray(other),
5692       objTag = objIsArr ? arrayTag : getTag(object),
5693       othTag = othIsArr ? arrayTag : getTag(other);
5694 
5695   objTag = objTag == argsTag ? objectTag : objTag;
5696   othTag = othTag == argsTag ? objectTag : othTag;
5697 
5698   var objIsObj = objTag == objectTag,
5699       othIsObj = othTag == objectTag,
5700       isSameTag = objTag == othTag;
5701 
5702   if (isSameTag && isBuffer(object)) {
5703     if (!isBuffer(other)) {
5704       return false;
5705     }
5706     objIsArr = true;
5707     objIsObj = false;
5708   }
5709   if (isSameTag && !objIsObj) {
5710     stack || (stack = new Stack);
5711     return (objIsArr || isTypedArray(object))
5712       ? equalArrays(object, other, bitmask, customizer, equalFunc, stack)
5713       : equalByTag(object, other, objTag, bitmask, customizer, equalFunc, stack);
5714   }
5715   if (!(bitmask & COMPARE_PARTIAL_FLAG)) {
5716     var objIsWrapped = objIsObj && hasOwnProperty.call(object, '__wrapped__'),
5717         othIsWrapped = othIsObj && hasOwnProperty.call(other, '__wrapped__');
5718 
5719     if (objIsWrapped || othIsWrapped) {
5720       var objUnwrapped = objIsWrapped ? object.value() : object,
5721           othUnwrapped = othIsWrapped ? other.value() : other;
5722 
5723       stack || (stack = new Stack);
5724       return equalFunc(objUnwrapped, othUnwrapped, bitmask, customizer, stack);
5725     }
5726   }
5727   if (!isSameTag) {
5728     return false;
5729   }
5730   stack || (stack = new Stack);
5731   return equalObjects(object, other, bitmask, customizer, equalFunc, stack);
5732 }
5733 
5734 module.exports = baseIsEqualDeep;

5749 /**
5750  * The base implementation of `_.isMatch` without support for iteratee shorthands.
5751  *
5752  * @private
5753  * @param {Object} object The object to inspect.
5754  * @param {Object} source The object of property values to match.
5755  * @param {Array} matchData The property names, values, and compare flags to match.
5756  * @param {Function} [customizer] The function to customize comparisons.
5757  * @returns {boolean} Returns `true` if `object` is a match, else `false`.
5758  */
5759 function baseIsMatch(object, source, matchData, customizer) {
5760   var index = matchData.length,
5761       length = index,
5762       noCustomizer = !customizer;
5763 
5764   if (object == null) {
5765     return !length;
5766   }
5767   object = Object(object);
5768   while (index--) {
5769     var data = matchData[index];
5770     if ((noCustomizer && data[2])
5771           ? data[1] !== object[data[0]]
5772           : !(data[0] in object)
5773         ) {
5774       return false;
5775     }
5776   }
5777   while (++index < length) {
5778     data = matchData[index];
5779     var key = data[0],
5780         objValue = object[key],

5782

5784       if (objValue === undefined && !(key in object)) {
5785         return false;

5791       }
5792       if (!(result === undefined
5793             ? baseIsEqual(srcValue, objValue, COMPARE_PARTIAL_FLAG | COMPARE_UNORDERED_FLAG, customizer, stack)
5794             : result
5795           )) {
5796         return false;
5797       }
5798     }
5799   }
5800   return true;
5801 }

6571 var compareAscending = __webpack_require__(17845);
6572 
6573 /**
6574  * Used by `_.orderBy` to compare multiple properties of a value to another
6575  * and stable sort them.
6576  *
6577  * If `orders` is unspecified, all values are sorted in ascending order. Otherwise,
6578  * specify an order of "desc" for descending or "asc" for ascending sort order
6579  * of corresponding values.
6580  *
6581  * @private
6582  * @param {Object} object The object to compare.
6583  * @param {Object} other The other object to compare.
6584  * @param {boolean[]|string[]} orders The order to sort by for each property.
6585  * @returns {number} Returns the sort order indicator for `object`.
6586  */
6587 function compareMultiple(object, other, orders) {
6588   var index = -1,
6589       objCriteria = object.criteria,
6590       othCriteria = other.criteria,
6591       length = objCriteria.length,
6592       ordersLength = orders.length;
6593 
6594   while (++index < length) {
6595     var result = compareAscending(objCriteria[index], othCriteria[index]);
6596     if (result) {
6597       if (index >= ordersLength) {
6598         return result;
6599       }
6600       var order = orders[index];
6601       return result * (order == 'desc' ? -1 : 1);
6602     }
6603   }
6604   // Fixes an `Array#sort` bug in the JS engine embedded in Adobe applications
6605   // that causes it, under certain circumstances, to provide the same value for
6606   // `object` and `other`. See https://github.com/jashkenas/underscore/pull/1247
6607   // for more details.
6608   //
6609   // This also ensures a stable sort in V8 and other engines.
6610   // See https://bugs.chromium.org/p/v8/issues/detail?id=90 for more details.
6611   return object.index - other.index;
6612 }

6783     stack.set(srcValue, objValue);
6784     baseMerge(objValue, srcValue, undefined, customDefaultsMerge, stack);

6798 var SetCache = __webpack_require__(52485),
6799     arraySome = __webpack_require__(90756),
6800     cacheHas = __webpack_require__(65581);
6801 
6802 /** Used to compose bitmasks for value comparisons. */
6803 var COMPARE_PARTIAL_FLAG = 1,
6804     COMPARE_UNORDERED_FLAG = 2;
6805 
6806 /**
6807  * A specialized version of `baseIsEqualDeep` for arrays with support for
6808  * partial deep comparisons.
6809  *
6810  * @private
6811  * @param {Array} array The array to compare.
6812  * @param {Array} other The other array to compare.
6813  * @param {number} bitmask The bitmask flags. See `baseIsEqual` for more details.
6814  * @param {Function} customizer The function to customize comparisons.
6815  * @param {Function} equalFunc The function to determine equivalents of values.
6816  * @param {Object} stack Tracks traversed `array` and `other` objects.
6817  * @returns {boolean} Returns `true` if the arrays are equivalent, else `false`.
6818  */
6819 function equalArrays(array, other, bitmask, customizer, equalFunc, stack) {
6820   var isPartial = bitmask & COMPARE_PARTIAL_FLAG,
6821       arrLength = array.length,
6822       othLength = other.length;
6823 
6824   if (arrLength != othLength && !(isPartial && othLength > arrLength)) {
6825     return false;
6826   }
6827   // Check that cyclic values are equal.
6828   var arrStacked = stack.get(array);
6829   var othStacked = stack.get(other);
6830   if (arrStacked && othStacked) {
6831     return arrStacked == other && othStacked == array;
6832   }
6833   var index = -1,
6834       result = true,
6835       seen = (bitmask & COMPARE_UNORDERED_FLAG) ? new SetCache : undefined;
6836 
6837   stack.set(array, other);
6838   stack.set(other, array);
6839 
6840   // Ignore non-index properties.
6841   while (++index < arrLength) {
6842     var arrValue = array[index],
6843         othValue = other[index];
6844 
6845     if (customizer) {
6846       var compared = isPartial
6847         ? customizer(othValue, arrValue, index, other, array, stack)
6848         : customizer(arrValue, othValue, index, array, other, stack);
6849     }
6850     if (compared !== undefined) {
6851       if (compared) {
6852         continue;
6853       }
6854       result = false;
6855       break;
6856     }
6857     // Recursively compare arrays (susceptible to call stack limits).
6858     if (seen) {
6859       if (!arraySome(other, function(othValue, othIndex) {
6860             if (!cacheHas(seen, othIndex) &&
6861                 (arrValue === othValue || equalFunc(arrValue, othValue, bitmask, customizer, stack))) {
6862               return seen.push(othIndex);
6863             }
6864           })) {
6865         result = false;
6866         break;
6867       }
6868     } else if (!(
6869           arrValue === othValue ||
6870             equalFunc(arrValue, othValue, bitmask, customizer, stack)
6871         )) {
6872       result = false;
6873       break;
6874     }
6875   }
6876   stack['delete'](array);
6877   stack['delete'](other);
6878   return result;
6879 }
6880 
6881 module.exports = equalArrays;

6900 /** `Object#toString` result references. */

6916     symbolValueOf = symbolProto ? symbolProto.valueOf : undefined;

6918 /**
6919  * A specialized version of `baseIsEqualDeep` for comparing objects of
6920  * the same `toStringTag`.
6921  *
6922  * **Note:** This function only supports comparing values with tags of
6923  * `Boolean`, `Date`, `Error`, `Number`, `RegExp`, or `String`.
6924  *
6925  * @private
6926  * @param {Object} object The object to compare.
6927  * @param {Object} other The other object to compare.
6928  * @param {string} tag The `toStringTag` of the objects to compare.
6929  * @param {number} bitmask The bitmask flags. See `baseIsEqual` for more details.
6930  * @param {Function} customizer The function to customize comparisons.
6931  * @param {Function} equalFunc The function to determine equivalents of values.
6932  * @param {Object} stack Tracks traversed `object` and `other` objects.
6933  * @returns {boolean} Returns `true` if the objects are equivalent, else `false`.
6934  */
6935 function equalByTag(object, other, tag, bitmask, customizer, equalFunc, stack) {
6936   switch (tag) {
6937     case dataViewTag:
6938       if ((object.byteLength != other.byteLength) ||
6939           (object.byteOffset != other.byteOffset)) {
6940         return false;
6941       }
6942       object = object.buffer;
6943       other = other.buffer;
6944 
6945     case arrayBufferTag:
6946       if ((object.byteLength != other.byteLength) ||
6947           !equalFunc(new Uint8Array(object), new Uint8Array(other))) {
6948         return false;
6949       }
6950       return true;
6951 
6952     case boolTag:
6953     case dateTag:
6954     case numberTag:
6955       // Coerce booleans to `1` or `0` and dates to milliseconds.
6956       // Invalid dates are coerced to `NaN`.
6957       return eq(+object, +other);
6958 
6959     case errorTag:
6960       return object.name == other.name && object.message == other.message;
6961 
6962     case regexpTag:
6963     case stringTag:
6964       // Coerce regexes to strings and treat strings, primitives and objects,
6965       // as equal. See http://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/7.0/#sec-regexp.prototype.tostring
6966       // for more details.
6967       return object == (other + '');
6968 
6969     case mapTag:
6970       var convert = mapToArray;
6971 
6972     case setTag:
6973       var isPartial = bitmask & COMPARE_PARTIAL_FLAG;
6974       convert || (convert = setToArray);
6975 
6976       if (object.size != other.size && !isPartial) {
6977         return false;
6978       }
6979       // Assume cyclic values are equal.
6980       var stacked = stack.get(object);
6981       if (stacked) {
6982         return stacked == other;
6983       }
6984       bitmask |= COMPARE_UNORDERED_FLAG;
6985 
6986       // Recursively compare objects (susceptible to call stack limits).
6987       stack.set(object, other);
6988       var result = equalArrays(convert(object), convert(other), bitmask, customizer, equalFunc, stack);
6989       stack['delete'](object);
6990       return result;
6991 
6992     case symbolTag:
6993       if (symbolValueOf) {
6994         return symbolValueOf.call(object) == symbolValueOf.call(other);
6995       }
6996   }
6997   return false;
6998 }

7019 /**
7020  * A specialized version of `baseIsEqualDeep` for objects with support for
7021  * partial deep comparisons.
7022  *
7023  * @private
7024  * @param {Object} object The object to compare.
7025  * @param {Object} other The other object to compare.
7026  * @param {number} bitmask The bitmask flags. See `baseIsEqual` for more details.
7027  * @param {Function} customizer The function to customize comparisons.
7028  * @param {Function} equalFunc The function to determine equivalents of values.
7029  * @param {Object} stack Tracks traversed `object` and `other` objects.
7030  * @returns {boolean} Returns `true` if the objects are equivalent, else `false`.
7031  */
7032 function equalObjects(object, other, bitmask, customizer, equalFunc, stack) {
7033   var isPartial = bitmask & COMPARE_PARTIAL_FLAG,
7034       objProps = getAllKeys(object),
7035       objLength = objProps.length,
7036       othProps = getAllKeys(other),
7037       othLength = othProps.length;
7038 
7039   if (objLength != othLength && !isPartial) {
7040     return false;
7041   }
7042   var index = objLength;
7043   while (index--) {
7044     var key = objProps[index];
7045     if (!(isPartial ? key in other : hasOwnProperty.call(other, key))) {
7046       return false;
7047     }
7048   }
7049   // Check that cyclic values are equal.
7050   var objStacked = stack.get(object);
7051   var othStacked = stack.get(other);
7052   if (objStacked && othStacked) {
7053     return objStacked == other && othStacked == object;
7054   }
7055   var result = true;
7056   stack.set(object, other);
7057   stack.set(other, object);
7058 
7059   var skipCtor = isPartial;
7060   while (++index < objLength) {
7061     key = objProps[index];
7062     var objValue = object[key],
7063         othValue = other[key];
7064 
7065     if (customizer) {
7066       var compared = isPartial
7067         ? customizer(othValue, objValue, key, other, object, stack)
7068         : customizer(objValue, othValue, key, object, other, stack);
7069     }
7070     // Recursively compare objects (susceptible to call stack limits).
7071     if (!(compared === undefined
7072           ? (objValue === othValue || equalFunc(objValue, othValue, bitmask, customizer, stack))
7073           : compared
7074         )) {
7075       result = false;
7076       break;
7077     }
7078     skipCtor || (skipCtor = key == 'constructor');
7079   }
7080   if (result && !skipCtor) {
7081     var objCtor = object.constructor,
7082         othCtor = other.constructor;
7083 
7084     // Non `Object` object instances with different constructors are not equal.
7085     if (objCtor != othCtor &&
7086         ('constructor' in object && 'constructor' in other) &&
7087         !(typeof objCtor == 'function' && objCtor instanceof objCtor &&
7088           typeof othCtor == 'function' && othCtor instanceof othCtor)) {
7089       result = false;
7090     }
7091   }
7092   stack['delete'](object);
7093   stack['delete'](other);
7094   return result;
7095 }

7418  * Once a property is set, additional values of the same property are ignored.

8147 var arrayReduce = __webpack_require__(6446),
8148     baseEach = __webpack_require__(52033),
8149     baseIteratee = __webpack_require__(89278),
8150     baseReduce = __webpack_require__(19356),
8151     isArray = __webpack_require__(19785);
8152 
8153 /**
8154  * Reduces `collection` to a value which is the accumulated result of running
8155  * each element in `collection` thru `iteratee`, where each successive
8156  * invocation is supplied the return value of the previous. If `accumulator`
8157  * is not given, the first element of `collection` is used as the initial
8158  * value. The iteratee is invoked with four arguments:
8159  * (accumulator, value, index|key, collection).
8160  *
8161  * Many lodash methods are guarded to work as iteratees for methods like
8162  * `_.reduce`, `_.reduceRight`, and `_.transform`.
8163  *
8164  * The guarded methods are:
8165  * `assign`, `defaults`, `defaultsDeep`, `includes`, `merge`, `orderBy`,
8166  * and `sortBy`
8167  *
8168  * @static
8169  * @memberOf _
8170  * @since 0.1.0
8171  * @category Collection
8172  * @param {Array|Object} collection The collection to iterate over.
8173  * @param {Function} [iteratee=_.identity] The function invoked per iteration.
8174  * @param {*} [accumulator] The initial value.
8175  * @returns {*} Returns the accumulated value.
8176  * @see _.reduceRight
8177  * @example
8178  *
8179  * _.reduce([1, 2], function(sum, n) {
8180  *   return sum + n;
8181  * }, 0);
8182  * // => 3
8183  *
8184  * _.reduce({ 'a': 1, 'b': 2, 'c': 1 }, function(result, value, key) {
8185  *   (result[value] || (result[value] = [])).push(key);
8186  *   return result;
8187  * }, {});
8188  * // => { '1': ['a', 'c'], '2': ['b'] } (iteration order is not guaranteed)
8189  */
8190 function reduce(collection, iteratee, accumulator) {
8191   var func = isArray(collection) ? arrayReduce : baseReduce,
8192       initAccum = arguments.length < 3;
8193 
8194   return func(collection, baseIteratee(iteratee, 4), accumulator, initAccum, baseEach);
8195 }
8196 
8197 module.exports = reduce;

8212  * running each element in a collection thru each iteratee. This method
8213  * performs a stable sort, that is, it preserves the original sort order of
8214  * equal elements. The iteratees are invoked with one argument: (value).
8215  *
8216  * @static
8217  * @memberOf _
8218  * @since 0.1.0

8248   }
8249   return baseOrderBy(collection, baseFlatten(iteratees, 1), []);

8264 /** Used as references for various `Number` constants. */

8273 /**
8274  * Invokes the iteratee `n` times, returning an array of the results of
8275  * each invocation. The iteratee is invoked with one argument; (index).
8276  *
8277  * @static
8278  * @since 0.1.0
8279  * @memberOf _
8280  * @category Util
8281  * @param {number} n The number of times to invoke `iteratee`.
8282  * @param {Function} [iteratee=_.identity] The function invoked per iteration.
8283  * @returns {Array} Returns the array of results.
8284  * @example
8285  *
8286  * _.times(3, String);
8287  * // => ['0', '1', '2']
8288  *
8289  *  _.times(4, _.constant(0));
8290  * // => [0, 0, 0, 0]
8291  */
8292 function times(n, iteratee) {
8293   n = toInteger(n);
8294   if (n < 1 || n > MAX_SAFE_INTEGER) {
8295     return [];
8296   }
8297   var index = MAX_ARRAY_LENGTH,
8298       length = nativeMin(n, MAX_ARRAY_LENGTH);
8299 
8300   iteratee = castFunction(iteratee);
8301   n -= MAX_ARRAY_LENGTH;
8302 
8303   var result = baseTimes(length, iteratee);
8304   while (++index < n) {
8305     iteratee(index);
8306   }
8307   return result;
8308 }

8414 /** Used as references for various `Number` constants. */
8415 var NAN = 0 / 0;
8416 
8417 /** Used to detect bad signed hexadecimal string values. */
8418 var reIsBadHex = /^[-+]0x[0-9a-f]+$/i;
8419 
8420 /** Used to detect binary string values. */
8421 var reIsBinary = /^0b[01]+$/i;
8422 
8423 /** Used to detect octal string values. */
8424 var reIsOctal = /^0o[0-7]+$/i;
8425 
8426 /** Built-in method references without a dependency on `root`. */
8427 var freeParseInt = parseInt;
8428 
8429 /**
8430  * Converts `value` to a number.
8431  *
8432  * @static
8433  * @memberOf _
8434  * @since 4.0.0
8435  * @category Lang
8436  * @param {*} value The value to process.
8437  * @returns {number} Returns the number.
8438  * @example
8439  *
8440  * _.toNumber(3.2);
8441  * // => 3.2
8442  *
8443  * _.toNumber(Number.MIN_VALUE);
8444  * // => 5e-324
8445  *
8446  * _.toNumber(Infinity);
8447  * // => Infinity
8448  *
8449  * _.toNumber('3.2');
8450  * // => 3.2
8451  */
8452 function toNumber(value) {
8453   if (typeof value == 'number') {
8454     return value;
8455   }
8456   if (isSymbol(value)) {
8457     return NAN;
8458   }
8459   if (isObject(value)) {
8460     var other = typeof value.valueOf == 'function' ? value.valueOf() : value;
8461     value = isObject(other) ? (other + '') : other;
8462   }
8463   if (typeof value != 'string') {
8464     return value === 0 ? value : +value;
8465   }
8466   value = baseTrim(value);
8467   var isBinary = reIsBinary.test(value);
8468   return (isBinary || reIsOctal.test(value))
8469     ? freeParseInt(value.slice(2), isBinary ? 2 : 8)
8470     : (reIsBadHex.test(value) ? NAN : +value);
8471 }

8531 /**
8532  * An alternative to `_.reduce`; this method transforms `object` to a new
8533  * `accumulator` object which is the result of running each of its own
8534  * enumerable string keyed properties thru `iteratee`, with each invocation
8535  * potentially mutating the `accumulator` object. If `accumulator` is not
8536  * provided, a new object with the same `[[Prototype]]` will be used. The
8537  * iteratee is invoked with four arguments: (accumulator, value, key, object).
8538  * Iteratee functions may exit iteration early by explicitly returning `false`.
8539  *
8540  * @static
8541  * @memberOf _
8542  * @since 1.3.0
8543  * @category Object
8544  * @param {Object} object The object to iterate over.
8545  * @param {Function} [iteratee=_.identity] The function invoked per iteration.
8546  * @param {*} [accumulator] The custom accumulator value.
8547  * @returns {*} Returns the accumulated value.
8548  * @example
8549  *
8550  * _.transform([2, 3, 4], function(result, n) {
8551  *   result.push(n *= n);
8552  *   return n % 2 == 0;
8553  * }, []);
8554  * // => [4, 9]
8555  *
8556  * _.transform({ 'a': 1, 'b': 2, 'c': 1 }, function(result, value, key) {
8557  *   (result[value] || (result[value] = [])).push(key);
8558  * }, {});
8559  * // => { '1': ['a', 'c'], '2': ['b'] }
8560  */
8561 function transform(object, iteratee, accumulator) {
8562   var isArr = isArray(object),
8563       isArrLike = isArr || isBuffer(object) || isTypedArray(object);
8564 
8565   iteratee = baseIteratee(iteratee, 4);
8566   if (accumulator == null) {
8567     var Ctor = object && object.constructor;
8568     if (isArrLike) {
8569       accumulator = isArr ? new Ctor : [];
8570     }
8571     else if (isObject(object)) {
8572       accumulator = isFunction(Ctor) ? baseCreate(getPrototype(object)) : {};
8573     }
8574     else {
8575       accumulator = {};
8576     }
8577   }
8578   (isArrLike ? arrayEach : baseForOwn)(object, function(value, index, object) {
8579     return iteratee(accumulator, value, index, object);
8580   });
8581   return accumulator;
8582 }
8583 
8584 module.exports = transform;

8881 /**
8882 * FUNCTION: isIntegerArray( value )
8883 *	Validates if a value is an integer array.
8884 *
8885 * @param {*} value - value to be validated
8886 * @returns {Boolean} boolean indicating if a value is an integer array
8887 */
8888 function isIntegerArray( value ) {
8889 	var len;
8890 	if ( !isArray( value ) ) {
8891 		return false;
8892 	}
8893 	len = value.length;
8894 	if ( !len ) {
8895 		return false;
8896 	}
8897 	for ( var i = 0; i < len; i++ ) {
8898 		if ( !isInteger( value[i] ) ) {
8899 			return false;
8900 		}
8901 	}
8902 	return true;
8903 } // end FUNCTION isIntegerArray()
